<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House to Urge Gun Purchase Checks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 27 (Xinhua) -- With the U.S. Supreme Court
having struck down a key portion of the Brady Act, one that forced
local sheriffs and police chiefs to conduct background searches on
handgun purchasers, the White House said Friday it will urge
states to continue to do them.
</P>
<P>
White House deputy press secretary Barry Toiv said President
Bill Clinton believes "strongly that if you do not get a criminal
background check, you should not get a gun," and will examine
possible new legislation to overcome the Supreme Court ruling.
</P>
<P>
Barry Toiv said Clinton ordered Attorney General Janet Reno and
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin to contact local law enforcement
authorities and "remind them" the Supreme Court ruling does not
prevent them from conducting their own background checks.
</P>
<P>
The Brady Law requires a mandatory waiting period before
handgun purchases to allow time for criminal background checks.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court, in its 5-4 decision, said the federal
government cannot force the states to administer a program to
enforce federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
The ruling left intact the waiting period, and therefore was
seen as affecting only a small number of relatively small states
that have not yet used instant computer background checks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
