<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greco-Cypriot Defense Pact Implemented as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Defense Minister Costas
Eliades said today that the joint defense pact between Greece and
Cyprus is being implemented as planned.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony here for Greek Cypriot officers who
graduated from military academies in Greece, Eliades said that
the joint defense pact is a cooperation agreement in the
military field within a joint defense plan to tackle a common
threat.
</P>
<P>
The pact, reached in November 1993 between Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides and the late Greek premier Andreas Papandreou,
provides Cyprus with sea, air and land cover from the Greek
military in the event of fresh offensives against the island.
</P>
<P>
Eliades noted that "the pact exists and is being continued as
originally planned."
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that the Greek Cypriot political
leadership has chosen to solve the Cyprus problem through
peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
He called on all countries interested in a viable and
permanent solution to the Cyprus problem to "seriously take into
account the Turkish sides' stance and policy."
</P>
<P>
Eliades was referring to recent violations of Cypriot air
space by Turkish military aircraft, which the Cypriot government
has protested to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Both Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash have
confirmed their participation in the U.N.-sponsored direct talks
between the two communities on the island, due to begin near New
York on July 9.
</P>
<P>
This eastern Mediterranean island has been divided since 1974
when Turkish troops invaded and took control of its northern
third in the wake of a pro-Athens coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
