<HEADLINE> Rival Parties in N.Ireland Hold Talks to Ease Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Rival Protestants and Roman
Catholics in Northern Ireland began their talks today to defuse
rising tension as "marching season" approaches.
</P>
<P>
The talks were held near the provincial capital Belfast after
suspected Irish Republican Army (IRA) guerrillas fired a rocket on
a police patrol in Belfast late Thursday. No one was injured by
the attack.
</P>
<P>
The disputed parade organized by the pro-British Protestants
will begin on July 6 at Drumcree near Portadown, but the
anti-British Catholics say such parades are anti-Irish and
inflammatory and should be confined to Protestant zones.
</P>
<P>
The marching season climaxes on July 12 when tens of thousands
of Protestants mark the 1690 "Battle of the Boyne" victory by King
William of Orange over the Catholic King James and his Irish
forces.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Mo Mowlam said today she would "leave no
stone unturned" to prevent a repeat of bloody clashes that swept
the divided province last year during the protestants' traditional
parade season.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam said in a statement that she and the participants wanted
"to find an honorable and principled accommodation on this
difficult issue."
</P>
<P>
"These proximity talks represent a genuine attempt, in good
faith, to find a way through a complex and highly emotive
problem," she added.
</P>
<P>
However, if no compromise is reached at the talks over the
Portadown parade, Mowlam and the police may be forced to ban it or
a rival "street festival" that the Catholics plan to stage in its
path.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair issued an ultimatum on
Wednesday to IRA, saying the peace talks will start in September
with or without IRA which has been barred from the multi-party
peace talks because it refused to call a cease-fire. If IRA agrees
to give up arms, it can be included in the peace negotiations that
is expected to end next May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
