<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Last Working Day in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 27 (Xinhua) -- With just the four days to go
before July 1 when Hong Kong returns to China, Hong Kong civil
servants had their last working day today.
</P>
<P>
Civil servants seemed to be more busy than ever in the Central
Government Office. Debbie Ho, chief information officer of the
Secretariat Press Office said, "From Saturday on, Hong Kong will
have a five-day holiday and the civil servants have to handle many
things today."
</P>
<P>
She said her colleagues were making preparations for the next
five days, not for vacationing but for lending a hand to those
arranging the Hong Kong Handover Ceremony and to those working in
the Press and Broadcast Center for the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The civil servants of the Economic Branch received their new
name cards today. After July 1, the Chief Secretary's Office will
be renamed Government Headquarters of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
Miss Ho said that her colleagues were very pleased to have
their new name cards on the last working day before Hong Kong's
handover.
</P>
<P>
At the reception hall of the Hong Kong Police Public Relations
Branch at Wanchai, Hong Kong Island, some staff workers were
removing the word "Royal" from the name of the Hong Kong Police.
</P>
<P>
A staff member said, "the removal has to be done today so that
after the holiday, our branch will have a new look."
</P>
<P>
At the gate of the Hong Kong Fire Services Headquarters
Building, some staff members were taking down the old logo of the
fire services and put on a new one.
</P>
<P>
Peter Hung Cheung-wing, senior information officer of the Fire
Services Department, said that the new logo is free of colonial
flavor, adding that it will be the most striking change to the
department after the handover.
</P>
<P>
He said that all the staff members of the department will be
busy preventing possible fires during the holidays.
</P>
<P>
He said that his department would try its best to ensure Hong
Kong people's safety in the transitional period.
</P>
<P>
Frank Chan Fan, a senior electronics engineer with the
Electrical and Mechanical Services Department, said that all the
staff members there would be at their posts after the five-day
holiday when Hong Kong will have become the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
He said that there will be no changes to his department except
for their name cards which bear the words "the government of the
HKSAR."
</P>
<P>
Today is also the last trading day at the Hong Kong Stock
Exchange. The Hang Seng Index increased 68.77 points to close at
15,196.79, hitting an all time high.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
