<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO to Send Extra Troops for September Polls in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Council (NAC),
NATO's top decision-making body, today decided to "temporarily"
reinforce the NATO-led peacekeeping force (SFOR) in Bosnia to
safeguard the planned municipal elections in September.
</P>
<P>
NATO spokesman Jamie Shea told reporters here that up to six
battalions would be sent to Bosnia to join the 35,000-strong
SFOR.
</P>
<P>
During an NAC meeting here today, it was decided that "no
significant changes to the size and capabilities" of SFOR would
take place until the NAC, in consultation with non-NATO SFOR
contributors, had thoroughly assessed the security situation in
Bosnia after the elections.
</P>
<P>
While the opposing parties in Bosnia remained in general
compliance with the military provisions of the Dayton peace
accord, the 16 NATO ambassadors, who constitute the NAC, together
with NATO Secretary General Javier Solana, expressed "serious
concerns" about the deficiencies remaining in the overall
implementation of the peace agreement which ended the near
four-year war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The 16 NATO countries reaffirmed that SFOR would provide the
general security framework for the elections as well as other
direct support to the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe (OSCE) which is overseeing the elections.
</P>
<P>
After Bosnia's municipal elections, SFOR's mission is expected
to enter the "Deterrence Phase, from the current "Stabilization
Phase", with a reduction in the number of soldiers to 20,000.
</P>
<P>
Replacing NATO's Implementation Force (IFOR) last December, SFOR
was mandated for an 18-month-long operation in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
So far, 36 countries have contributed to SFOR, including the 16
NATO members and 20 non-NATO countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
