<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Economy Gains at 5.9 Percent Pace in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. economy expanded at a
quicker pace of 5.9 percent in the first three months of this
year, U.S. Commerce Department said in its final report today.
</P>
<P>
It was the fastest growth rate in nearly 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The final report on the economy growth in the first three
months represented an improvement over last month's 5.8 percent
estimate for the gross domestic product (GDP) and April's 5.6
percent figure.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that the economic boom, which built on robust
growth of 3.8 percent in the final three months of last year, was
driven by consumers.
</P>
<P>
The consumer spending, which represents about two-thirds of
U.S. GDP, expanded at a 5.6 percent annual rate last quarter, the
best in five years.
</P>
<P>
Housing construction and spending by businesses on new
buildings and equipment also contributed to the big jump in GDP
early this year.
</P>
<P>
And the growth came with an inflation gauge tied to the GDP
advancing at a moderate 2.7 percent annual rate.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the economy probably won't grow this strongly
again for quite some time. They're predicting second-quarter
growth will register around a moderate 2 percent as consumers take
a breather from their spending spree of early in the year.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown appears to be coming just in time to dissuade the
U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed) from increasing short-term interest
rate to keep inflation tame.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Fed policy-makers, who increased short-term interest rate
by a quarter percentage point in March 25, will meet on early July
to decide the monetary policy in the second half of this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
