<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Concludes Interim Agreements with Georgia, Armenia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union's executive body, adopted on Friday a decision to
conclude the Interim Agreements with Georgia and Armenia on behalf
of the European Coal and Steel Community and Euratom.
</P>
<P>
A Commission spokesman said that this would allow the two
Interim Agreements to enter into force within the next two months.
</P>
<P>
The Interim Agreements put into force the trade-related
provisions of the Partnership and Co-operation Agreements between
the EU and these two countries, which have yet to be ratified.
</P>
<P>
The Interim Agreements formally liberalize trade in goods other
than steel, textiles and coal, offers both sides Most Favored
Nation treatment regarding tariffs and duties, and also provides
for mutual assistance in customs matters.
</P>
<P>
Georgia and Armenia commit themselves to raise protection of
intellectual property rights to European levels.
</P>
<P>
"The guarantees of the Interim Agreement will stimulate growth
in bilateral trade and is an excellent basis for the further
integration of these two countries in the global economy," EU's
Foreign Affairs Commissioner Hans van den Broek commented.
</P>
<P>
EU's Interim Agreements with Georgia and Armenia were signed
respectively in October and December last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
