<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Welcomes Damascus Declaration FMs' Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Iran today expressed welcome to
the joint statement issued Thursday by the foreign ministers
of Damascus Declaration Signatories and termed it as a "positive"
sign in relations between Iran and Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency IRNA today published a statement by
Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi, in which he
said the readiness and interest of the Damascus Declaration states
in improving relations with Iran could be considered as a
"positive sign."
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said "such an issue would not only be in line with
expansion of cooperation among regional states, but would also be
the sole way of guaranteeing security in the sensitive region of
the Persian Gulf and of helping promote international peace and
security."
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting of foreign ministers of Damascus
Declaration states, which include Egypt, Syria, Bahrain, Kuwait,
Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates (UAE),
ended Thursday in Syria's Mediterranean resort of Lattakia.
</P>
<P>
In their joint statement, the foreign ministers emphasized the
sovereignty of the United Arab Emirates (UAE) over the three Gulf
islands of Abu Moussa and Greater and Lesser Tunbs in its dispute
with Iran, calling on both sides to enter into serious talks for a
peaceful solution to this issue.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian spokesman expressed his hope that the fading away
of certain Arab countries' optimism toward Israel would strengthen
Arab cooperation and Islamic solidarity for defending the
legitimate rights of Palestinians and liberation of the Arab
occupied lands.
</P>
<P>
He said that the ongoing dispute between Iran and the UAE over
the three islands of Abu Moussa, Greater and Lesser Tunbs at the
mouth of the strategic Hormuz Strait, which are claimed by both
Iran and the UAE, could be solved on the basis of the 1971
agreement.
</P>
<P>
He added that "Arab countries should strive for encouraging
the UAE to continue talks with Iran and to refrain from making
mistakes in evaluation of cooperation priorities and in spotting
the dangers which threatened the Arab world."
</P>
<P>
However, he said the three islands are inseparable parts of
Iran and any claim on their ownership could only weaken Islamic
solidarity and strengthen Israel and foreign forces in the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
