<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Ambassador Briefs German Media on Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Ambassador to Germany Lu
Qiutian stressed here today that the Chinese government will hold
on to the "one country, two systems" principle and will do its
best to guarantee stability and property of Hong Kong after its
return to the motherland on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference in Bonn, Lu said: "The return of
Hong Kong is an event of historic importance" which will enable
the Chinese people to put an end to an over-100-year-old disgrace
and realize the long-term wish for reunification.
</P>
<P>
After giving an overview over Hong Kong's history and its
recent development, Lu expressed confidence in Hong Kong's future.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Chinese government will make every effort
to preserve stability and prosperity of Hong Kong because it is
not only in the interests of Hong Kong, but also in the interests
of China as a whole.
</P>
<P>
In order to carry on the successful reform and opening-up
policy, China needs Hong Kong as a bridge leading to the world.
Meanwhile Hong Kong also serves as a bridge for the world to gain
access to the huge Chinese market, Lu said, adding that Hong Kong
also needs the mainland as a market and a vast hinterland for its
stable development.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ambassador dismissed as "groundless" some
international scepticism about Hong Kong's democracy, civil rights
and press freedom after its return to the motherland, stressing
that the Chinese government will make all its efforts to practice
the policies of "one country, two systems" in Hong Kong, let "Hong
Kong people govern Hong Kong" and let them enjoy "a high degree of
autonomy".
</P>
<P>
"China is fully aware that the concept of allowing two
different social, political and economic systems to coexist in one
country will pose a great challenge to us," Lu said. But "the
development of the last 13 years give us the courage and
confidence that we will be able to bring it to a success," he
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
