<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Stock Market Attract More Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Mutual fund investors continued
to pour money into stock funds in the U.S. this month, the Wall
Street Journal reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the fund industry, which covers stock, bond
and money markets, may have already topped 4 trillion U.S. dollars
under management.
</P>
<P>
A mutual-fund trade group reported that fund investors had
shoveled 20.14 billion U.S. dollars into stock funds in May, more
than previously estimated and a jump of 28 percent from April's
total of 15.71 billion. May turned out to be the second-biggest
month this year for stock-fund sales.
</P>
<P>
The fund industry had 3.9 trillion U.S. dollars under
management at the end of May, up from 3.73 trillion U.S. dollars
in April. Given this month's inflows and the sharp rise in the
stock market, the industry may have reached the 4 trillion mark
already, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
The New York stock market has grown by about 20 percent so far
this year, with the Dow Jones industrial average nearing 7,700
points this morning, compared with the 6,440 at the start of the
year.
</P>
<P>
The rapid expansion of the stock market coupled with much
improved services of brokerage companies and other service
providers are the key to the fast increase of funds, according to
some fund experts.
</P>
<P>
A growing number of securities companies are investing huge
funds to install new computers and put their services onto
Internet and other forms of computer networks, making it possible
for investors to trade at home. In addition, companies providing
electronic trading also charge less service fees than the
traditional over-the-counter or telephone ordering means.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts estimated that by the year 2000, the electronic
traded funds in U.S. can reach 500 billion U.S. dollars, about
five times greater than the present standard.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, 1.5 million accounts were set up
electronically, according to a research group. They involved 111.4
billion U.S. dollars. But the number of electronic accounts is
expected to increase by 1.3 million this year, an amazing pace for
the industry, the group said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
