<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SIB Chairman Looks Forward to New Era for Regulation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The planned merger of banking
supervision and the self-regulatory organizations (SROs) into the
Securities and Investments Board (SIB) is an "exciting
opportunity", Sir Andrew Large, chairman of the SIB said today.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the system of two-tier City regulation for
causing delays in resolving financial scandals such as the
misselling of personal pensions.
</P>
<P>
Introducing the SIB's Annual Report for 1996/97, Sir Andrew
argued that the two-tier system, which the government is to
reform, has "serious defects" and is "inherently less efficient
and effective than it could be".
</P>
<P>
The chairman welcomed the Government's decision to transfer the
functions of the SROs to an enhanced SIB, saying that the existing
two-tier system was "flawed" and had led to duplication.
</P>
<P>
Sir Andrew said the case for reforming the structure of
regulation under which SROs such as the Securities and Futures
Authority are monitored by SIB, became "overwhelming" because of
its flaws.
</P>
<P>
There has been "not just independence but hostility" among
regulatory organizations, which has made it more difficult to
clear up the pensions misselling, and co-ordinate responses to
financial failures such as that of Barings.
</P>
<P>
"Even the regulatory response to the conduct of certain UK
firms in world copper markets, which is generally seen as a
considerable success, could have been more robust under a more
cohesive structure," Sir Andrew stated.
</P>
<P>
However, Sir Andrew also said that in spite of the
inefficiencies caused by the two-tier system of regulation, over
the last five years the regulators had secured higher standards in
many areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
