<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-27 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Earns 4 billion Dollars in Oil Revenue in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Oil Minister Gholamreza
Aqazadeh announced here today that Iran earned 4 billion
U.S. dollars by exporting oil in the first quarter of the
current Iranian calendar year starting March 21, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency IRNA quoted the minister as saying
that the revenue had been achieved under the circumstances that
the oil market has not been in a desirable status.
</P>
<P>
The minister expressed his hope that the decision of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) to keep the
current production ceiling and member quotas would help improve
prices, especially in the fall and winter seasons.
</P>
<P>
The OPEC ended Vienna talks Thursday with a new freeze on its
production limits that stand at 25.03 million barrels per
day (bpd).
</P>
<P>
However, OPEC's 11 members have increased production by more
than 2 million bpd since November last year, reaching 27.05
million bpd in April this year. The oil prices dropped due to the
increase of international production and the decrease of demand.
</P>
<P>
Iran earned hard currency of 19.5 billion dollars from oil
export in the last fiscal year, registering an increase of 21.87
percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Iran, the world's fourth largest oil producer and the second
largest oil exporter, is expected to generate 18.5 billion
dollars by exporting 2.5 million bpd during this fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
As for the projects implemented by his ministry in the areas
of oil and gas and for renovation and expansion of the related
installations, Aqazadeh said that all the damages inflicted on
the oil and gas sectors during the eight-year war between Iran
and Iraq (1980-88) had been repaired and favorable investments
have been made in the oil, gas and petrochemical sectors.
</P>
</TEXT>
