<HEADLINE> Iraq Vows to Cooperate with UN Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has vowed to continue to
cooperate with U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan to implement
U.N. resolutions, the official Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported
today.
</P>
<P>
It said that Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz, who is
visiting the U.N. at present, vowed to the U.N. chief at their
meeting Thursday that Iraq will cooperate with him in the
implementation of the oil-for-food deal as well as other
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food deal, signed last year between Iraq and the
U.N., allows Iraq to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil over
six months on a renewable basis to raise cash for humanitarian
goods urgently needed in the country after nearly seven years of
U.N.-imposed sanctions for Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The first six-month period expired on June 7 and the deal
was extended for another six months.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting Wednesday with Richard Butler, who will replace
Rolf Ekeus as executive chairman of the U.N. Special Commission
(UNSCOM) on Iraq, Aziz expressed the hope to build good relations
with him.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the U.N. adopted a resolution condemning Iraq for
hindering the UNSCOM arms inspectors' missions and warned Iraq
that it will face even tougher penalties if it failed to
cooperate fully with the inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is not allowed to have weapons of mass destruction,
including missiles with ranges beyond 150 kilometers, after
its troops were defeated in the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM accused Iraq of still hiding a considerable number
of the banned weapons, but Baghdad denied such allegations.
</P>
</TEXT>
