<HEADLINE> British, Irish PMs to Meet in London on Ulster Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Ireland's new Prime Minister Bertie
Ahern is to meet his British counterpart Tony Blair on Thursday
in a bid to put a fresh impetus to the Northern Ireland peace
process, press reports from Dublin said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the first between Ahern and Blair, will take place
against a background of mounting tension in Northern Ireland as
the start of the annual season of Protestant parades and marches
next weekend approaches.
</P>
<P>
Irish government officials were reported as saying this evening
that the meeting was agreed in a lengthy telephone conversation
between the two leaders this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Ahern, who was elected the country's new Prime Minister on
Thursday after a cliffhanger election victory, has made it clear
that ending the Northern Ireland conflict, in which 3,200 people
have died since 1969, would be the top priority of the new
government.
</P>
<P>
The two governments have agreed that Sinn Fein, the political
wing of the Irish Republican Army (IRA), should not be allowed to
attend the all-party peace talks on the future of Northern Ireland
unless IRA guerillas called an end to its bombing campaign against
British rule of the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
