<HEADLINE> Iraq Calls on Damascus Declaration States to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has called on the foreign
ministers of the Damascus Declaration states to change their
positions toward the country.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahaf told the Iraqi
News Agency Thursday that the foreign ministers of the Damascus
Declaration states, who concluded a meeting in the Syrian city
of Latakia on the same day, have repeated the "same big mistake"
which they previously committed against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, Syria and the six Gulf states signed the declaration
in 1991 after the Gulf War which was triggered by Iraq's
invasion of Kuwait, in a bid to establish a new Gulf security
mechanism and strengthen the region's economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahaf urged the Damascus Declaration states to stop making
"false" accusations against Iraq and "seriously" consider
correcting their positions against the country.
</P>
<P>
He described as "false and groundless" the allegation by the
Latakia conference that Iraq has done acts of provocation against
 Kuwait and the neiboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, the minister said, has repatriated all Kuwaiti POWs and
others immediately after the 1991 Gulf war. And in the past few
years, it has returned all the Kuwaiti properties taken by the
Iraqis during their invasion of Kuwait, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Kuwaiti government insisted that Iraq still holds
about 600 Kuwaiti prisoners and missing persons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
