<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Decides to Extend Mandate of UNFICYP in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. security Council
this morning decided to extend the mandate of the United Nations
Peace-keeping Force in Cyprus for a further six months until
December 31.
</P>
<P>
By unanimously adopting Resolution 1117, the Council called on
the military authorities to refrain from any action, particularly
in th vicinity if the buffer zone, which could exacerbate
tensions.
</P>
<P>
In the resolution, the Council stressed its supports for the
Secretary-General's mission of good office and the importance of
working with him towards an overall comprehensive settlement.
</P>
<P>
Calling on the leaders to commit themselves to the process of
negotiation, the Council stressed that full support of all
concerned was necessary for the negotiation process to produce
results.
</P>
<P>
It urged the continuation of the efforts of the United Nations
and other concerned to promote the holding of bicommunal events to
build trust and mutual respect between the two communities.
</P>
<P>
It also expressed its grave concern about the excessive levels,
expansion, upgrading and modernization of the military forces and
armaments in Cyprus, and the lack of significant reduction in the
number of foreign troops in the country, which threaten to raise
tensions both on the island and in the region, and complicate
efforts to negotiate an overall political settlement.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council reiterated its position that a settlement
must be based on a state of Cyprus with a single sovereignty and
international personality and a single citizenship, with its
independence and territorial integrity safeguarded, and comprising
two politically equal communities in a bicommunal and bizonal
federation.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been virtually partitioned since 1974 when Turkish
troops landed in the north in reaction to a coup in Nicosia by
the military government then ruling Greece. The United Nations has
since then trying to reunite the island on the agreed basis of a
bicommunal and bizonal federation.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. force now comprising 1,200 troops has been stationed in
Cyprus since i964 and patrols a buffer zone across the island.
</P>
</TEXT>
