<HEADLINE> Clinton to Visit Poland, Romania After NATO Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
will visit Poland and Romania after next month's summit of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the 16-member alliance will invite the first group
of former Warsaw Pact states to join. Clinton is due to attend
the summit on July 8-9 before going to Poland and Romania.
</P>
<P>
These visits, like the Madrid summit, are part of the
president's efforts to help build an "undivided" and "secure"
Europe in the next century, the White House said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has said it favors admitting the Czech Republic,
Poland and Hungary into NATO in the first wave of expansion. But
the Europeans upholds Romania and Slovenia should also join.
</P>
<P>
Clinton would go to Warsaw to symbolize "the historic
importance" of NATO expansion and remind it and other new members
of their alliance obligations, White House spokesman Michael
McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Bucharest, the first by a U.S. president to
the Romanian capital in two decades, Clinton will make clear that
Romania is a "leading candidate for future entry" into NATO,
McCurry added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is scheduled to leave the U.S. for Europe on July 5,
after the July 4 Independence Day celebration and is due to return
to the United States July 12. 
</P>
</TEXT>
