<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Signs Legislation on Anti-drug Grants Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Friday signed legislation, making neighborhoods with successful
anti-drug programs eligible for federal matching grants of up to
100,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which passed Congress in May with a near-unanimous
vote, was designed to extend the anti-drug war to neighborhoods
where, despite federal efforts, drug abuse has increased among
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that the legislation does not mean a lessening of
law enforcement efforts to curb drug use or to stop drugs from
entering the country.
</P>
<P>
But he said, "Clearly it sends a signal that we are shifting
emphasis to recognize that we will never get a hold of this
problem unless we deal with the demand side here in America."
</P>
<P>
He said young people experimenting with drugs have to realize
that "they are playing a dangerous game and that we have to try to
do more than we have in the past to stop it."
</P>
<P>
The new law authorizes the Office of National Drug Control
Policy to rechannel existing federal drug-control funds into 143.5
million dollars in neighborhood grants over five years.
</P>
<P>
Grants would go to local communities with "sustainable and
accountable" anti-drug programs. But the efforts must involve all
sectors of a community, including families, businesses, news
media, schools, law enforcement, health care professionals and
religious leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
