<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delegates Still Deadlocked on Earth Summit Document </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Delegates attending the
19th special U.N. session on the environment and development were
still deadlocked today on a final document, sources close to the
session said.
</P>
<P>
The five-day meeting, which went until 5 a.m. today, is due to
end at midnight EDT (0400 GMT). Delegates from more than 170 U.N.
member states, including 70 heads of state and government,
attended the session, dubbed the Earth Summit.
</P>
<P>
Even a 26-point political statement, the result of several
rounds of consultations before the session began, may be thrown
out because of differences on several issues, including objectives
for increasing foreign aid, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
There are still major differences on such topics as global
warming and financial targets for helping poor countries.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton Thursday pledged to lead his
country in reduction of greenhouse gases and contribute 1 billion
U.S. dollars over the next five years to help developing nations
reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
</P>
<P>
But many environmentalists were deeply disappointed that he did
not present a specific plan to reduce the greenhouse gases as
European Union nations have done.
</P>
<P>
The EU nations have challenged the United States by proposing a
15 percent reduction in emissions below the 1990 level by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries have been calling for increase of
financial assistance for developed nations in improvement of the
environment and development of economy.
</P>
<P>
Most industrial countries pledged at the 1992 Rio Summit to
increase foreign aid to 0.7 percent of their gross national
product, a goal on the U.N. agenda since 1972. But aid has fallen
to below 0.3 percent, especially in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
