<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Call For Elimination of Riverblindness by 2007 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the World Bank and
some other world organizations today called for the elimination of
Riverblindness throughout Africa by the year 2007 at the unveiling
of a bronze statue depicting an African adult blinded by
riverblindness being led by a child,.
</P>
<P>
The statue was unveiled by Anna-Maria Fati Paul, a Ghanaian
riverblindness survivor, and James D. Wolfensohn, president of the
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
A declaration signed by World Bank President Wolfensohn, former
U.S. former President Jimmy Carter, leaders of the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP), the World Health Organization (WHO),
the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) and other development
partners called for strong support and "whatever action is
required" to achieve the elimination of riverblindness as a major
public health problem and socioeconomic development constraint in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
The event also celebrated the 10th anniversary of the decision
taken by Merck &AMP; Co., Inc. to provide the most effective drug
against the disease, Mectizan, free of charge, to as many who need
it, for as long as it is needed, to protect against the disease.
If successful, the program could reach as many as 50 million
people within the coming decade.
</P>
<P>
Riverblindness, also known as onchocerciasis or "the lion's
stare," is a leading cause of blindness in Africa. It is caused by
a parasitic worm -- transmitted by the black fly, which lives and
reproduces for up to 14 years in the human body. Victims often
become blind by the time they have reached their mid-30s.
</P>
<P>
According to World Bank background materials, the disease is
found in sub-Saharan Africa, Yemen and parts of Central and South
America, but is most prevalent in the Savannah areas of West
Africa. It is estimated that over 100 million people remain at
risk of infection, 18 million are still heavily infected and 1
million are heavily sight impaired or blind.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank, joined hands by the WHO, FAO and UNDP, launched
the Onchocerciasis Control Program (OCP) in 1974 in seven West
African countries in the largest infested area in the world. Four
more countries and more than 20 donors have since joined the
program. The program consisted of weekly aerial sprayings of
larvacide along 189,000 km of rivers in a bid to destroy the black
fly larvae. In the 1980s, a drug called ivermectin or Mectizan was
found to be effective at paralyzing and expelling the infant worms
in the body and, as a result, halting the progress of the disease.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the World Bank launched a new program -- the African
Program for Onchocerciasis Control -- to expand the control to 19
African countries. The new program is modeled after the OCP and
its goal is to eliminate the disease in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
