<HEADLINE> Giant Dragon Lantern Lights Up to Mark Hong Kong's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The open-air square in front of
the Cultural Center at the Tsim Sha Tsui, in Kowloon, was filled
with a large crowd tonight when a 3.5-kilometer-long dragon
delineated with neon lights was lit up.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the lighting-up ceremony, Rita Fan, chairman of the
Provisional Legislative Council of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region, expressed the hope that Hong Kong will take
off as the giant dragon.
</P>
<P>
This show is considered the biggest lantern show in Hong Kong
that features the return of Hong Kong to China.
</P>
<P>
The dragon head, made by craftsmen in Foshan, Guangdong
Province, is six meters high, nine meters long and three meters
wide. The dragon, formed with two million light bulbs, bears nine
smaller dragons symbolizing Kowloon, with its head facing Victoria
Harbor at Tsim Sha Tsui and its tail at the Boundary Street.
</P>
<P>
"The dragon light designs we are watching today are different
in meaning from those we only can see during the Christmas
festivals," Fan said.
</P>
<P>
It shows the spirit in which that all Hong Kong people are
celebrating this historical event, she added.
</P>
<P>
Also attending the ceremony were Wulan Mulun, deputy director
of the Hong Kong Branch of the Xinhua News Agency, and Leung
Oi-sie, secretary of Justice of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region Government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
