<HEADLINE> Komen Wins 5,000m at Kenya Trials for World Champs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Daniel Komen won the 5,000
meters at Kenya's national trials for the world championships on
Saturday while quite a few greats suffered shock defeats.
</P>
<P>
Komen triumphed with 13 minutes 23.8 seconds, beating Tom
Nyariki, who clocked 13:25.1, and Paul Bitok, who was timed at
13:27.0.
</P>
<P>
But some top performers including Olympic 3,000m steeplechase
champion Josephat Keter were well beaten in their specialities.
</P>
<P>
Double 5,000m world champion Ishmael Kirui was the first
casualty, clocking 13:46.0 for sixth place in the event.
</P>
<P>
In the 800m event, Olympic bronze medalist Fredrick Onyancha
finished a moderate seventh place.
</P>
<P>
Big names to fall in the 1,500 meters included Barcelona
Olympics 800m champion William Tanui, who was in fourth place and
Martin Keino, who finished in a poor sixth place in 3:40.5.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan selectors delayed naming the team for the world
championships in Athens in August until July 16 when top
athletes will have completed their Grand Prix assignments.
</P>
<P>
Under current Kenya Amateur Athletic Association rules, the
first two finishers automatically qualify while the third finisher
will be based on training. 
</P>
