<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renault Sticks to Controversial Belgian Plant Closure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 28 (Xinhua) -- French carmaker Renault today made
the final decision to stick to its controversial proposal to close
an assembly plant in Belgium by the end of July, rejecting union
proposals for shorter working hours or job cuts.
</P>
<P>
The decision came two weeks after the automaker, under pressure
from France's new Socialist government, named an independent team
of experts to find alternatives to closing the 3,100-man Vilvoorde
plant, which provoked a storm of political and union protest when
it was announced in February.
</P>
<P>
Renault, the country's second biggest carmaker, argued the
closure was part of a fundamental restructuring plan following the
group's 5.25 billion-franc (909.3 million U.S. dollars) loss in
1996.
</P>
<P>
Danielle Kaisergruber, head of the experts' team which studied
the Vilvoorde plant, said that reductions in working hours and
staffing "does not represent an alternative" to closing the plant,
which she said was a "structural" decision.
</P>
<P>
Renault, the world's 10th largest automaker, said it would
offer compensation to laid-off workers and maintain an undefined
"activity" in Vilvoorde which is expected to employ 400 Belgian
workers.
</P>
<P>
Some jobs would also be made available to Vilvoorde staff in
its plants in France, notably in Douai and Maubeuge near Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Louis Schweitzer, Renault's president, promised to continue
negotiations with Belgian unions on the terms of compensation, the
establishment of a working group to convert the plant into a new
enterprise, and French jobs to be given to Vilvoorde workers.
</P>
<P>
The closure of the assembly plant, first announced by
Schweitzer on February 27, triggered violent protests from the
company's 10,000 workers across Europe.
</P>
<P>
The factory is in the hometown of Belgian Prime Minister
Jean-Luc Dehaene, who had appealed to France's Socialist Premier
Lionel Jospin for a review of the closure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
