<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Briefs on Activities Greeting Return of Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Following are the news in brief
concerning activities greeting the return of Hong Kong on July 1:
</P>
<P>
Treaty-Signing Site Lures Visitors
</P>
<P>
Jinghai Temple in Nanjing, the capital of east China's Jiangsu
Province, has seen an increase in the number of visitors from all
over the country these days, because it is the site of the
humiliating Nanking Treaty, which resulted in the ceding of Hong
Kong to Britain in 1842.
</P>
<P>
Centenarian Sends Telegram to Hong Kong Government
</P>
<P>
Hou Youcheng, the 100-year-old Honorary Chairman of the
Municipal Committee of the People's Political Consultative
Conference of Xiaoyi City in Shanxi province, recently sent a
telegram of congratulations to the government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) for the return of the
territory.
</P>
<P>
Hou said he hopes to see the day when Macao returns and the
reunification between the two sides across the Taiwan Strait is
realized.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Flower "Blossoms" in Tibet
</P>
<P>
The bauhinia, the regional flower of Hong Kong, is appearing
everywhere in the Tibet Autonomous Region as local people put the
flower in their songs, paintings, and handicrafts to greet the
return of Hong Kong to the motherland on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The HKSAR regional flags with the bauhinia in the middle have
sold out in local shops, and many students participating in local
painting contests have painted the bauhinia as a show of their
enthusiasm for Hong Kong's return. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
