<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tehran Suffers Serious Air Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The mayor of Tehran said here today
that the air pollution in the Iranian capital is by far more
polluted than other cities in the developing world.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Gholamhossein Karbaschi said at a two-day international
conference that the per capita carbon produced in Tehran is twice
as much as in other places in the third world.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Tehran Radio said that some 4,000 people die
every year due to respiratory problems caused, or exacerbated, by
pollution and another 2,000 die of cancer at the same time because
of pollutants in the air, including lead.
</P>
<P>
Specialists said that 70 percent of air pollution in Tehran
caused by vehicles -- everyday there are 7 million liters of
petroleum and 1.5 million liters of gas oil consumed by 1.5
million vehicles, including buses and motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
Iran's First Vice-President Hassan Habibi stressed in the
meeting that precise evaluation of ways to reduce air pollution in
the capital is "an absolute necessity."
</P>
<P>
"Timely tune-up of the engines, increase in the number of
buses and mini-buses, and expansion of electrical bus lines across
Tehran are ways to reduce air pollution," Habibi said.
</P>
<P>
There are now two major electrical bus lines operating in
eastern Tehran which have been established as the first step to
bring air pollution under control.
</P>
<P>
Government financing is also available to car owners who want
to convert their car's fuel from petroleum to liquid gas. The
conversion costs about 350 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The government finances half of the conversion costs. Once
converted, a car's liquid gas tank can be filled as many times as
it is necessary for only 5,000 Rials, or about 1.6 U.S. dollars,
per month.
</P>
<P>
However, some 15 liquid gas filling stations established across
the city can not respond to the demands by thousands of taxi cab
drivers and private car owners.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tehran municipality has declared this year "the
lead-free year," encouraging car owners to use the unleaded super
petroleum sold at gas stations at the same rate as regular
petroleum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 8 Million AIDS Orphans in Sub-Saharan Africa, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations report said
more than 90 percent of the 9 million children who have lost
their mothers to AIDS live in sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. report released Friday by joint U.N. HIV/AIDS
program, listed Uganda and Zimbabwe as some of the countries
where children orphaned by AIDS are becoming a major problem,
said a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Experts in Zimbabwe estimate that by 1996 approximately 8
percent of children in Uganda are in this situation. ''In Uganda,
1,000 children every week lost one of their parents, to AIDS,''
said the report.
</P>
<P>
It said, millions of children around the world are
increasingly living under the threat of HIV/AIDS epidemic, with
1,000 children becoming infected with AIDS daily.
</P>
<P>
According to figures estimated by the United Nations, one
million children under the age of 15 will be living with the
virus by the end of 1997, and AIDS may increase infant mortality
by 75 percent and under five child mortality by more than 100
percent.
</P>
<P>
''AIDS is the most recongnized disease in the world today,''
Peter Piot, Executive Director of the United Nations program on
HIV/AIDS warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
