<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China to Catch up With More Developed East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Provinces in central China are
making an effort to catch up with the more developed eastern part
of the country, and the Beijing-Kowloon Railway, which began
operation early this year, has become the latest force in this
effort.
</P>
<P>
The railway, whose purpose was to speed up economic development
in central China by linking up with Hong Kong, runs along a
nine-province economic belt, whose infrastructure, natural
resources, and labor force have been made better use of, and which
have attracted investors as a result.
</P>
<P>
Twelve overseas financial organizations have opened offices in
Wuhan, the capital of Hubei province and the heart of central
China. By March, the city had used a total of 4.8 billion US
dollars worth of foreign investment, which contributed more than
35 percent of the city's input in fixed assets.
</P>
<P>
Henan province, to the north, had 2.57 billion US dollars in
overseas investment last year, while Hunan province, to the south,
used more than 75 percent of overseas funds for infrastructure and
industrial improvements.
</P>
<P>
The central government has also begun to shift its economic
development strategy to central and western parts of the country.
From 1993 to the end of May this year, the State Development Bank
provided 224.8 billion yuan in loans to the area, accounting for
more than 60 percent of the total number of loans.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Project along the Yangtze River and the
Xiaolangdi Project along the Yellow River, are helping economic
growth in central China, cultivating new economic growth areas in
machinery, electronics, and building materials.
</P>
<P>
The GDPs of Henan and Hubei now rank among the country's 10
largest, and the nine central China's provinces had 1.9 trillion
yuan in GNP last year, contributing 28 percent to the nation's
total. Their economic growth rate was 0.9 percent higher on
average than was east China's.
</P>
<P>
Economists have begun to talk about better prospects for the
area, saying they believe that central China will become as
economically active in the early 21st century as east China did in
the 1980s and early 1990s.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
