<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Metro's No. 1 Line Opens First Section </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The first section of Metro No. 1
in Guangzhou City, capital of south China's Guangdong Province,
opened to traffic today, and is viewed as a gift from Guangzhou
for the return of Hong Kong to the motherland, according to local
officials.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou is now China's fourth city with a subway, after
Beijing, Tianjin and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The first section has five stations and is 5.4 km long. The
total length of the No. 1 Line will be 18.4 km and will cost 12.7
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The subway is being built as part of the effort to ease the
increasing traffic jams in this economic and political center of
south China, with a population of over six million.
</P>
<P>
The No. 1 Line will be able to handle 1.13 million passengers
a day, accounting for 10-15 percent of the city's daily urban
passenger flow.
</P>
<P>
Most of the equipment used in the metro was imported and funds
came from the German, US, British, and Japanese governments. Part
of the cost was covered by loans from international banks or
raised through real estate deals in areas along the subway.
</P>
<P>
Local experts say that the fund-raising methods may be used by
other Chinese cities that plan to build subways but are plagued by
a shortage of funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
