<HEADLINE> CIA, Israeli Agents Spy in Northern Iraq: INA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Iraq said today that agents of the
U.S. Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) and Israeli intelligence
service have entered northern Iraq to conduct espionage.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency (INA) said here today that some CIA and
Israeli agents have recently entered northern Iraq under the
cover of working with the Red Crescent Committees.
</P>
<P>
After their arrival, the agents began to contact with key
figures and sheikhs in the area and try to bribe them in return
for their cooperation, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Some of the key figures and sheikhs have absolutely refused to
cooperate with those agents, confirming their affiliation to the
Iraqi central government, it added.
</P>
<P>
The situation in northern Iraq has been complicated since the
defeat of Iraq by the U.S.-led allied forces in the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The region, called Kurdistan and populated by Iraqi Kurds, now
is out of the control of Baghdad and under the protection of the
U.S.-led allies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
