<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Britain Agree on Transfer of HK Government Assets, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 28 (Xinhua) -- China and Britain signed here
today a minute on the arrangements for the transfer of the assets
and liabilities of the Hong Kong government.
</P>
<P>
According to this Agreed Minute on the Question of the
Arrangements for the Transfer of the Assets and Liabilities of the
Hong Kong Government, the British government, in line with the
Sino-British Joint Declaration, shall transfer all assets and
liabilities of the Hong Kong government while returning Hong Kong
to China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the joint declaration and the Basic Law of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), the Chinese
government has decided to authorize the HKSAR government to take
over all assets and liabilities of the Hong Kong government, other
than the Exchange Fund which is governed by a separate Agreed
Minute.
</P>
<P>
The assets and liabilities of the Hong Kong government will be
transferred to the HKSAR government on the commencement of July 1,
1997, the Minute notes.
</P>
<P>
The HKSAR government shall take charge of auditing these assets
and liabilities, and manage them on its own in accordance with
relevant laws of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
After the signing of the Minute, Zhao Jihua, senior Chinese
representative of the Sino-British Joint Liaison Group, said that
the transfer of the assets and liabilities of the Hong Kong
government is a major component of the transfer of power in Hong
Kong, as well as a concrete action of the Chinese and British
sides to implement the joint declaration.
</P>
<P>
"I am sure that the signing of the Minute will contribute to
the smooth transition of Hong Kong," he commented.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Central Bank Governor on Financial Relations with HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, June 28 (Xinhua) -- China's central bank governor Dai
Xianglong said here today that he believes Hong Kong is able to
stabilize its financial market after July 1.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark in an interview with Xinhua. "China's
interior will not use the foreign currency reserves of Hong Kong
or its other assets," Dai said.
</P>
<P>
He described five principles the Central Bank will follow in
financial relations with Hong Kong:
</P>
<P>
First, the renminbi (RMB), the official currency, will be
treated as foreign currency if used in Hong Kong, and the Hong
Kong dollar, as foreign currency in China's inland areas.
</P>
<P>
Second, Hong Kong will maintain its independent system of
currency after July 1. The Hong Kong dollar will continue to be
freely convertible without foreign exchange controls. The Central
Bank supports the idea of its being pegged to the US dollar. The
RMB is convertible under the current account. The State
Administration of Foreign Exchange will control foreign exchange
in accordance with the law.
</P>
<P>
Third, the relationship between the monetary authorities of
China's interior and Hong Kong will be relatively independent. The
Hong Kong Monetary Authority will be responsible to the government
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR). The
Central Bank will not take the place of the Hong Kong Monetary
Authority nor will it set up branches in Hong Kong. The monetary
authorities of the inland and Hong Kong will maintain and expand
their relations of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Fourth, the HKSAR government will continue to be responsible
for the management of financial agents in Hong Kong and in China's
inland areas. Hong Kong financial agents in the inland will be
regarded as foreign-funded financial agents, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong financial agents in inland areas enjoy the same
preferences as foreign financial organizations in China. Hong Kong
branches of inland's financial bodies enjoy no privileges in Hong
Kong and must abide by local laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
Fifth, financial affairs between China's inland areas and Hong
Kong will be conducted according to international financial
practices. Debt and credit between banks and enterprises of the
two places will continue to be dealt with as foreign debt and
credit. Inland enterprises listed on the Hong Kong stock market
will be treated as overseas listings. These enterprises must
observe Hong Kong laws and rules. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
