<HEADLINE> Doohan Calls for Rain Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Reigning 500cc world champion
Michael Doohan had the Dutch Grand Prix halted after 11 of the 20
laps in Assen, the Netherlands on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 32-year-old Doohan, winner of five of the six races this
season, waved to race organisers that the conditions were not
suitable to carry on the race.
</P>
<P>
"I tried to keep going to complete 66 percent of the race which
would have counted full points, but I had to slow down so much on
the 11th lap that it was pointless to carry on," Doohan said.
</P>
<P>
The organisers were hoping to restart the race provided the
rain went away which would leave current second Carlos Checa of
Spain requiring a 3.73 seconds win over Doohan in the second 'leg'
to take the Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
Rain played havoc with the race last year forcing two 'legs'
which Doohan won beating Alex Criville, who was forced out of this
year's renewal with an injured hand following a fall in practice
on Thursday. 
</P>
