<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Paper Ordered to Pay 10 million Shillings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan High Court yesterday
ordered the local weekly newspaper " The People " to pay a record
10 million Kenyan Shillings (about 188,000 U.S. Dollars) to a
Nairobi businessman for defamation.
</P>
<P>
This is the highest award of damages for libel in Kenya's
legal history, the local daily "East African Standard" reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the judgement, Justice Emmanuel O'Kubasu has said
that the freedom of press "must be exercised and enjoyed in a
responsible manner."
</P>
<P>
Careless and malicious reporting cannot be tolerated by the
law, he stressed, adding that "this court will not be slow in
awarding to those whose reputations have been dented."
</P>
<P>
Justice O'Kubasu entered judgement against the publishers
after the paper failed to enter appearance and defense within the
prescribed period.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan businessman Joshua Kulei, who is President Daniel arap
Moi's personal assistant, sued the paper over an article
published last January entitled "Asian Link in Moi's Kitchen
Cabinet".
</P>
<P>
The story read in part that "before the recent shake-up in the
government positions among those regarded as the key members of
the Kitchen Cabinet were... State House operative Joshua Kulei...
Each of these has a retinue of Asian businessmen who seek
assistance to get government contracts and other public funded
deals that require political patronage to go through..."
</P>
<P>
The paper alleged that topping the list of Asian businessmen
linked to Kulei is Pankoj Somaia who spends most of his time in
Kenya's port city Mombasa where Kulei has lucrative contracts
with the Kenya Ports Authority.
</P>
<P>
In his suit filed on February 18, Kulei said that the story
was understood to mean he was dishonest and corrupt, adding that
the allegations in the story had ruined his name and that his
family had been affected.
</P>
<P>
He had sought an order for a permanent injunction to restrain
the publishers from publishing articles which may be injurious on
him and also sought up to 23 million Shillings for defamation,
exemplary damages and costs of the suit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
