<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Return Means a Step Toward National Reunification: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's return to the motherland
means China takes a significant step forward in the course of the
national reunification, a senior Chinese official said.
</P>
<P>
Guo Jiading, chief representative of the Chinese side of the
Sino-Portuguese Joint Liaison Group (JLG), told Xinhua in a recent
interview that Hong Kong's return will have positive influence
over the transitional procedure in Macao.
</P>
<P>
The 66-year-old ambassador said that Hong Kong's smooth return
to the motherland shows the determination and capability of the
Chinese government and people in the course of national
reunification.
</P>
<P>
"It also sets a model for the international community in
handling disputes left over from the past," said Guo.
</P>
<P>
He said he himself experienced the bitterness in the time when
China was bullied by the imperialists and colonialists before
1949. After the birth of New China in 1949, he began his
40-year-long diplomatic career.
</P>
<P>
During the negotiations between China and Britain on the Hong
Kong issue, Guo participated in the translation and making of the
final version of the Sino-British Joint Declaration.
</P>
<P>
"To see the return of Hong Kong to the embrace of the
motherland, I feel very excited," he told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said the success of the concept "one country, two
systems" in Hong Kong offers an example for Macao, and helps
increase Macao residents' confidence in realizing a stable
transition and a smooth transfer of power in 1999.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it will also push forward the cooperation between
China and Portugal in settling all urgent issues concerning
Macao's transition as soon as possible, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Currently, he said, a lot of transitional affairs need to be
resolved, especially, the localization of civil service and law as
well as the use of Chinese as an official language.
</P>
<P>
"The localization of senior and middle ranking civil service,
in particular, is lagging far behind the requirements for a smooth
transfer of power," he said, adding, "The work on the transfer of
archives and government assets should be started as soon as
possible."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
