<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Residents to Continue Enjoying Travel Freedom: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Regina Ip Lau Suk-yee, Director
of Immigration of the Hong Kong government, today denied the rumor
that Hong Kong residents' freedom of entrance and exit will be
restricted after July 1.
</P>
<P>
"In accordance with the Basic Law, Hong Kong residents shall
enjoy free movement within the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR), as well as the freedom to travel and to enter or
leave the region," said Ip, who will retain her current post in
the HKSAR government after the handover.
</P>
<P>
Starting from July 3, she said, the HKSAR Department of
Immigration will issue SAR passports to permanent Hong Kong
residents who are Chinese nationals and have the right of abode in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"We are the sole department that has the right to issue the SAR
passport," she stressed.
</P>
<P>
Since it started to accept applications on June 10, the
Department of Immigration has received more than 700,000
application forms for the SAR passport designed with advanced
anti-counterfeit techniques.
</P>
<P>
"By last Thursday, many countries had announced preferential
treatment for SAR passport holders. Thirty-three of them have
decided to grant visa-free access to such holders," Ip said,
predicting that more countries and regions will announce the same
arrangements soon.
</P>
<P>
She said that Hong Kong will continue its existing visa-free
regime after July 1, and that at present, residents of over 170
countries and regions can come to Hong Kong and stay for seven
days to six months without a visa.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Hong Kong was visited by 11 million foreigners, and
visas were granted to some 14,000 foreign professionals and
investors.
</P>
<P>
"These entrepreneurs, professionals and people with special
skills brought with them funds, techniques and expertise to Hong
Kong, thus benefiting Hong Kong's economic growth," said Ip,
adding that the figure has also reflected the confidence of the
international community in Hong Kong's future.
</P>
<P>
She revealed that her department is now working out a new
program to make it easier for tourists and business people to
visit Hong Kong, so that Hong Kong will be in a better position to
maintain its status as an international trade, financial and
tourism center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
