<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Warns of Military Option Against S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from west African
countries have warned to impose sanctions, and use force against
Sierra Leone military junta, if it fails to return power to
ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah "within a reasonable time".
</P>
<P>
If sanctions in the form of an economic embargo did not work, force
could be used, with the agreement of heads of state of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS), according to press reports
today.
</P>
<P>
According to a 14-point communique following the one-day meeting in
Conakry, Guinea, a four-member committee comprising ministers from
Nigeria, Ghana, Guinea and Cote d'Ivoire was designated to implement
the decisions of the meeting with the approval of the ECOWAS chairman,
Nigeria's head of state General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
The committee, which will also include representatives from the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) secretariat, has been empowered to
negotiate with the junta led by Major Johnny Paul Koroma on the
peaceful transfer of power to Kabbah and to report back to General
Abacha within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers called on the international community not to
recognize the military government in Sierra Leone, but to provide
emergency aid and other form of assistance to Guinea and other
neighboring countries affected by the new wave of refugees after the
May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
They also called for international support to the ECOWAS initiative
in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
In its reaction, the junta's spokesman, Colonel Abdul Sesay, said
it welcomed the prospects of a visit by ECOWAS delegation to Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
The visit, together with the OAU secretariat, will give them
"opportunity to see things for themselves on the ground".
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone, a member of ECOWAS, was not represented at the
Conakry meeting on Thursday. But the decision of the foreign ministers
of the other 15 ECOWAS countries was conveyed to Kabbah, who
reportedly welcomed the plans for his reinstatement.
</P>
<P>
The ousted president applauded the decision to restore his
government and ultimatum of two weeks within which the negotiation
with the coup leader should take place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
