<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bigger Inflow of Inland Fund Benefits Hong Kong's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Increases of investment in Hong
Kong from the interior areas of China will benefit Hong Kong's
economic development, Donald Tsang Yam-kuen, financial secretary
of Hong Kong, said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news briefing at the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center, Tsang said that after Hong Kong's return to
China, closer economic ties between the interior areas and Hong
Kong will provide more opportunities for the inflow of investment
into Hong Kong from the mainland.
"This will have no negative impact on Hong Kong's economy," he
said. "On the contrary, it will speed up economic development in
Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
He welcomes more inland companies to list on the Hong Kong
Stock Exchange or set up branches in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that they should abide by local laws and
regulations just as investors from elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Tsang, who will serve at the same post in the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR), spoke highly of economic development
momentum in China's interior areas, where economic growth has been
higher than in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
It is conducive to narrowing the gap between the two sides and
offers more opportunities for bilateral cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tsang said he is confident in Hong Kong's future.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong recorded a six percent economic growth in the first
quarter of this year, he said, predicting an annualized growth
rate of 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Growth of Hong Kong's banking and insurance sectors will be
above the average. In general, prospects in the 1997-98 period are
good, he said.
</P>
<P>
Stipulations of the Basic Law that guarantee the independent
operation of Hong Kong's economy have laid a legal foundation for
Hong Kong's sustained prosperity, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said it is important for Hong Kong to maintain an open
industrial and commercial system, low tariffs and its status as an
international financial center.
</P>
<P>
The future HKSAR government will continue to support
development of the private sector and provide funds for
infrastructure development and education, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
