<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PRC's Central Bank Won't Interfere in HK Monetary Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, June 28 (Xinhua) -- China's central bank governor Dai
Xianglong said here today that the People's Bank of China will not
interfere in the operation of the monetary market in Hong Kong
after it returns to the motherland on July 1.
</P>
<P>
However, the central bank is ready to provide support to
stabilize Hong Kong's currency in time of need and in response to
the Hong Kong Monetary Authority's request, he added.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Dai said after July 1 China's
interior and Hong Kong will come under the same sovereignty but
they will still have separate currencies and monetary systems and
each will have its own financial regulatory body.
</P>
<P>
According to the Basic Law, Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR) will provide an appropriate economic and legal
environment for the maintenance of Hong Kong's status as an
international financial center, Dai said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Hong Kong dollar shall continue to circulate
as the region's legal tender and there shall be no change in the
present system of issuing currency. Markets for foreign exchange,
gold, securities and futures will remain open, and the free flow
of capital will be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
Dai said that Hong Kong's foreign exchange fund will be
controlled by the HKSAR government and used mainly to regulate the
Hong Kong dollar's exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
"After the handover, Hong Kong can keep and develop its
financial ties with foreign countries and regions under the name
of "China Hong Kong".
</P>
<P>
It can join international financial organizations, sign or
continue to honor bilateral and multilateral financial agreements
and open financial representative offices in other countries, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"With regard to activities by international organizations that
only accept sovereign states but involve Hong Kong, the central
government will consult with HKSAR and include its personnel as
members of the Chinese delegation," said the central bank
governor." This will help consolidate Hong Kong's status as a
world financial center." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
