<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Have High-Degree Autonomy in Maintaining Social order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
HONG KONG, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) will have a high-degree of autonomy in
maintaining law and order under the principle of "one country, two
systems", Secretary for Security Peter Lai Hing-ling said here
today.
</P>
<P>
He told a news briefing that in accordance with the Basic Law,
the Hong Kong SAR government will be responsible for the
maintenance of the public order whereas the military forces
stationed by the Central government shall not interfere in local
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Three days prior to the inauguration of the Hong Kong SAR
government, the secretary for security, who will retains his post
after Hong Kong's return to China, vowed to keep Hong Kong police
force as one of the best in the world.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong police will continue to win the faith from the
public and prepare themselves for the challenge in the years
ahead.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong will continue to enjoy the autonomy and authority in
regulating the inflow and outflow of goods and people, and the
people from China's interior areas will have to enter into Hong
Kong in an orderly and appropriately administrative way, he added.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the continued implementation of the liberal visa
regime in a bid to stabilize the metropolis' status as an
international trade, banking and tourism center and, with regard
to the passport issue of the Hong Kong SAR, he told reporters that
the Immigration Department started to accept applications
beginning June 10 and would issue the passports from July 3, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The immigration Department of the Hong Kong SAR is vested with
full authority to process applications, maintain records and issue
the HKSAR passports, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many countries have announced to treat HKSAR
passport favorably, with 33 of them promising to grant free-visa
access to Hong Kong SAR passport holders.  
</P>
</TEXT>
