<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Typhoon Kills One in Southern Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June (Xinhua) -- A medium-sized typhoon hit Japan's main
southern island of Kyushu this morning, triggering heavy downpours
and causing massive domestic flight cancellations, the
Meteorological Agency said.
</P>
<P>
A 44-year-old nurse in Usuki, Oita Prefecture, drowned after
she fell into a river, police said.
</P>
<P>
The season's eighth typhoon, which hit Nishisonogl Peninsula,
Nagasaki Prefecture, shortly after 9 a.m. local time, is heading
northeast at a speed of about 35 kilometers per hour and is
expected to strike Japan's largest island of Honshu.
</P>
<P>
It had sustained winds of 108 kph at its center and a central
air pressure of 975 hectopascals, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Major Japanese Airlines, including Japan Airlines, All Nippon
Airways and Japan Air System said they have canceled some 270
domestic flights scheduled for Saturday, while railway officials
said train services in the Kyushu region are being sharply
curtailed.
</P>
<P>
All ferry operations between Fukuoka and the South Korean city
of Pusan were canceled.
</P>
<P>
The agency forecast that the typhoon would zap central Honshu
before leaving the Japanese archipelago on Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
The typhoon is expected to dump between 250 to 300 millimeters
of rainfall on the Tokai region and Kinki regions and 200
millimeters on the Katon and Tohoku region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
