<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 28 (Xinhua) -- A steady drizzle delayed the
scheduled starting time of play at Wimbledon tennis championships
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the bad weather prevented any play for the second
consecutive day, the first time this has happened since 1909. And
now, the tournament is now running some 250 matches behind
schedule.
</P>
<P>
A decision on whether the gates will be opened to allow play on
Sunday, traditionally a rest day, will be taken later today.
Organisers have been reluctant to go ahead with the extra day's
play because of the chaos caused the only other time they did so
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
But tournament referee Alan Mills said: "It will depend very
much on the weather forecast for Sunday." 
