<HEADLINE> Japanese Cities Protest Against U.S. Planned Nuclear Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese cities of Hiroshima and
Nagasaki, the world's only two cities attacked by atomic bombs in
World War II, today protested against a U.S. plan to carry out a
subcritical nuclear experiment on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In response to a report that the United States will hold a
subcritical nuclear test in the state of Nevada to help check the
quality of nuclear weapons, the two cities urged Washington to
think twice, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
"I regret that the test will be carried out despite requests by
a lot of Japanese local governments and people to suspend it, I
want to ask the U.S. again to suspend the experiment," Kyodo
quoted Hiroshima Mayor Takashi Hiraoka as saying.
</P>
<P>
Criticizing Washington's move, Nagasaki Mayor Itcho Ito said,
"It is an act of treason against the international community for
the U.S. to hold such a test at this time, I want to protest
strongly against it."
</P>
<P>
On August 6, 1945, the world's first atomic bomb to be used in
warfare was dropped from U.S. aircraft on Hiroshima in western
Japan, destroying about 90 percent of the city and killing about
200,000 people. Three days later, a similar bomb was dropped on
Nagasaki in southwestern Japan, leaving some 140,000 dead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
