<HEADLINE> Britain to Remain Neutral in Kenya's General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The British government would
remain neutral in Kenya's impending general elections, Tony
Lloyd, the visiting British Minister of State for Foreign and
Commonwealth Affairs, has claimed.
</P>
<P>
"Britain will not seek sides in Kenya's elections despite the
fact that we have a legitimate interest" as one of the key
investors in the eastern African country, said Lloyd Friday, the
final day of his three-day visit to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The British government firmly believed that the general
elections are for the Kenyan people alone, and need not be
interfered with by foreigners, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, Britain is hoping to see free, fair and
violence-free elections in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after meeting with Kenyan President Daniel
arap Moi, Vice-President George Saitoti, opposition leaders and
the church members.
</P>
<P>
There is a need to cool off the heightening pre-election
political temperature and start dialogue between the government
and the opposition, he noted, urging the two sides to resolve
their differences in a peaceful manner.
</P>
<P>
Lloyd hoped that the church and other non-political
organizations in Kenya would play a mediatory role in
solving the differnces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
