<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Narrows Current-Account Shortfall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 28 (Xinhua) -- South Korea saw its current account
shortfall abating significantly in May largely thanks to
decreasing imports.
</P>
<P>
The statistics released by the Bank of Korea (BOK) show that
the nation's current account deficit amounted to some 1.04 billion
U.S. dollars in May, a remarkable improvement over the 1.59
billion dollar shortfall a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Since the start of this year, the deficit narrowed from some
3.06 billion dollars in January to about 2.5 billion dollars in
February, 2.21 billion dollars in March and further to over 1.71
billion dollars in April.
</P>
<P>
The aggregate current account shortfall came to some 10.52
billion dollars during the first five months of 1997.
</P>
<P>
South Korea registered a trade deficit of 364 million dollars
in May.
</P>
<P>
With the steadily increasing exports against the shrinking
imports, the nation's current account shortfall is expected to
reach some 11.5 billion dollars in the first half of 1997, and
stand below the BOK's forecast of 18 billion dollars for all this
year, a BOK official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Treatment Wins Ground in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- China's decision to grant national
treatment to overseas investors two years ago has proved
successful in attracting foreign funds to help economic
development.
</P>
<P>
When China threw its doors open in the late 1970s, it tried to
woo overseas investors with a policy combining tax concessions and
necessary restrictions.
</P>
<P>
While China has made itself a powerful magnet for overseas
capital, foreign investors have, on the other hand, insisted on
enjoying what is called national treatment, which would remove
certain restrictions.
</P>
<P>
National treatment provides the overseas investors with a level
playground and enables them to compete on the same footing with
domestic companies, said Mike Burns, an investor from Texas of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
As they no longer enjoy tax exemption and reduction in China,
overseas investors can recover their lost ground through benefits
in national treatment, such as the lowering of tariff rates,
removal of extra fees, and provision of easier market access, an
official of China's Ministry of Finance (MOF) said.
</P>
<P>
"It's a sort of give-and-take arrangement," said an
international investor, who asked not to be identified, in an
interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
She added that giving national treatment to overseas investors,
which means withdrawal of both favorable policy incentives and
restrictions, indicates that the Chinese market is ripening and
China now can compete internationally in terms of luring overseas
capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Continues Offensives Against Muslim Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Philippine troops today continued
their clearing operations in Mindanao, the southern Philippines,
in search of fleeing Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) rebels
who were believed behind many kidnapping cases, the military said.
</P>
<P>
At early dawn today, a group of MILF rebels blocked again
several cargo trucks and passenger vehicles along a national
highway in Pagalunga town in Maguindanao province.
</P>
<P>
Capt. Noel Detoyato, spokesman for the Sixth Infantry Division
in charge of the clearing operations, said the rebels felled an
electric post to block the highway, leading to the closure of
traffic in the area.
</P>
<P>
Many commuters were stranded as the rebels held the area for
two hours before they fled, Detoyato said, adding that the
military has already advised commuters to avoid travelling at
night or early dawn.
</P>
<P>
On early Thursday morning, some 1,000 MILF rebels held hostage
about 100 bus passengers in nearby North Cotabato province, along
the same highway stretching across southern Mindanao. Around 60
hostages were freed by the military, but dozens of others remain
in captivity.
</P>
<P>
Detoyato also confirmed that an undetermined number of MILF
rebels Friday launched rocket attacks on Camp Rajamuda in Pikit
town, North Cotabato province, which was overrun by government
troops Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The sporadic attacks resulted in four injuries on the
government side, he said.
</P>
<P>
In Carmen, Cotabato, a group of unidentified armed men Friday
held 60 villagers as human shields against pursuing government
troops.
</P>
<P>
Detoyato said the military has strengthened defense in villages
in North Cotabato and Maguindanao to prevent further
hostage-taking incidents and retaliatory attacks against civilians
by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
As the military operations went on in Mindanao, the sixth round
of peace talks between the government and the MILF did not push
through today as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
The MILF leadership decided to postpone the talks soon after
the military took Camp Rajamuda Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaffar, MILF vice chairman for political affairs, said
today they will not go back in the negotiating table until the
situation in Mindanao normalized.
</P>
<P>
Jaffar reiterated his warning that the MILF will go to a
full-scale war if the military operations escalated in their other
"controlled-areas."
</P>
<P>
A total of 158 rebels, soldiers and civilians have been killed
since fighting broke out June 16 between government troops and the
MILF in central Mindanao, the military said.
</P>
<P>
The continued fighting has forced more than 60,000 residents to
flee their homes and seek refuge in temporary evacuation centers.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
