<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Treatment Wins Ground in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When China decided to give national treatment to overseas
investors two years ago, the Chinese government selected Shenzhen,
Xiamen, the Pudong New Area of Shanghai, Hainan Province and the
coastal city of Dalian, in northeast China's Liaoning Province, to
try out the program.
</P>
<P>
Official surveys show that with the policy shift some
overseas-funded enterprises have successfully expanded their sales
in China and reduced their cost in water and power consumption.
</P>
<P>
A Sino-Japanese kinescope company in Shenzhen, a special
economic zone neighboring Hong Kong, is such an example. It has
pulled itself out of the red and turned itself into a leading
color tube producer in China, after the city government granted
local joint ventures national treatment and removed the ban on the
sale of their products on the home market.
</P>
<P>
Li Decheng, vice mayor of Shenzhen, said that the SEZ has
decided to open the home market even wider to products from
overseas-funded ventures.
</P>
<P>
"Those technically-advanced enterprises and joint ventures in
agriculture can sell all their products at home," he said.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen, another SEZ, which is in eastern Fujian Province, and
Hainan, China's largest SEZ, have also promulgated detailed
measures to give national treatment to overseas investors. These
measures include raising the proportion of products allowed to be
sold in China, extending the terms of operation and business scope
of overseas-funded enterprises, and permitting overseas partners
to hold larger stakes in joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
"Such experiments have proved to be highly successful and paved
the way for implementing it nationwide by the end of the century,"
said Gao Guanjiang, a research fellow with the Development
Research Center of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show the five special economic zones actually used
more than 6.8 billion US dollars in overseas capital last year,
and overseas investment in Shenzhen and Zhuhai alone surged more
than 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, Gao also pointed out that China's infrastructure
sector still needs to implement preferential policies and attract
sufficient overseas funds for building roads, docks and electric
power plants.
</P>
<P>
"To reduce the impact that the policy of national treatment may
exert on the inflow of foreign funds in certain sectors, we should
still combine opening the market and abolishing certain
preferential policy incentives," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
