<HEADLINE> India's Industry Growth Registers Sharp Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 28 (Xinhua) -- India's industrial growth
plummeted to 6.7 percent in 1996-97, down from the previous year's
11.6 percent, the times of India reported today.
</P>
<P>
The performance was well below the official target of a double
digit growth rate for 1996-97, but it comes as no surprise to
industry watchers here because the last one month (April 1997) has
seen a lot of leading companies announcing poor financial results
of the year.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown was evident in the manufacturing sector as it grew
by eight percent in 1996-97, considerably down from the previous'
growth rate of 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to some analysts, the slowdown should really be
termed as a recession and is due to constraints like
infrastructural deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown seems to be continuing in the current fiscal year,
the Times of India said, quoting a government announcement.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures released on Friday, mining grew
only 1.2 percent in a "certain period under consideration" in the
current fiscal, compared to 7.4 percent during the previous
period.
</P>
<P>
Electricity grew only 3.8 percent, compared to eight percent in
the previous comparable period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
