<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Ratify U.N. Pact on Landmines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Kenya will ratify the U.N.
Convention banning the use of anti-personnel landmines, Kenya's
Attorney-General Amos Wako was quoted by local press reports as
saying today.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government made the decision after deliberation
among President Daniel arap Moi and other top governmental
officials, Wako said Friday when attending an exhibition on the
impact of landmines.
</P>
<P>
So far Kenya is one of the few mine-free countries on the
African continent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Geoff Loane, the head of the International
Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) regional delegation, said the
ICRC intends to use Kenya as the base to spearhead its campaign
against planting of anti-personnel landmines in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The ICRC's choice of Kenya is partly due to the political
stability the country has enjoyed after independence in early
1960s, said Loane.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 120 million landmines laid worldwide while
a further 100 million are lying in warehouses waiting to be
planted, Loane said.
</P>
<P>
Of all the landmines around the world, over one third are
found in Africa, leaving some 18 countries on the continent faced
with the scourge of mines, he added.
</P>
<P>
So far 92 countries have signed the Declaration of Brussels
preparing a first-ever landmine ban treaty to be signed in
Ottawa, Canada in December, according to a report reaching here
from Brussels.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, facilitated by the international landmine talks
starting in Ottawa at the end of 1996, is obliged to ban the
production, use, stockpiling and transfer of anti-personnel
landmines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Services to Continue Leading HK Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The service industry is expected
to continue playing a central role in Hong Kong's economy.
</P>
<P>
K. Y. Tang, a Hong Kong government economist, told a press
briefing here today that people employed in the local service
industry accounted for 80 percent of Hong Kong's total workforce
last year, from 55 percent in 1986, and that the proportion of the
industry's output value in Hong Kong's GDP rose to 84 percent in
1995, from 70 percent a decade before. Also, between 1986 and
1996, Hong Kong's export of services registered an annual growth
of eight percent.
</P>
<P>
With an accelerated shift of Hong Kong's economy from
manufacturing to services, Tang said, the service industry is
expected to play an even bigger role in the local economy.
</P>
<P>
He said new technologies have been introduced for use by the
service industry, boosting efficiency. The local service industry
covers telecommunications, trade, cargo container transport, wharf
construction, and financial services, among others.
</P>
<P>
Financial and business services such as banking, insurance and
real estate have all recorded fast growth over the past few years,
Tang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
