<HEADLINE> 10 Military Personnel Killed in Explosion in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Ten Turkish military personnel
were killed in a mine explosion in southeastern Turkey on Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
One sergeant, eight soldiers and one village guard aboard a
vehicle were killed when the mine planted by rebels of the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) exploded, said the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency today.
</P>
<P>
The explosion took place when the military vehicle was on its
way to relieve guard between Yayvantepe village and Botas-DS 4
Pumping Station in Midyat town of Mardin province linking Syria.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a group of PKK members attacked a passenger minibus
in Genc town of eastern province of Bingol the same evening,
wounding three people, according to Anatolia.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has enhanced its armed attacks on the government
military targets in southeastern Turkey since some 50,000-strong
government troops intruded northern Iraq from May 14, attempting
to raid the PKK militants, who have set up their shelters in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Sources here who declined to be named said that Turkey has
withdrawn most of its troops from the cross-border military
operations in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The military campaign reportedly followed a request for help
by Mesud Barzani, leader of Iraq's Kurdistan Democratic Party
(KDP) to sweep the PKK rebels out of the region.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military said that at least 2,500 PKK guerrillas
have been killed since the Turkish security forces crossed into
northern to wipe out the rebel group in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting an almost 13-year-old separatist
war for autonomy and over 23,000 people were killed in the
clashes in eastern and southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
