<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania: Farm Input Tax Waived, Car Tax Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Customs duty and sales tax
on fertilizer, veterinary drugs and plant chemicals have been
waived in Tanzania with immediate effect, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Finance Minister Daniel Yona announced the
government decision at the National Assembly on Friday, when
winding up the 1997-98 fiscal year's budget proposals and the
development plan.
</P>
<P>
Yona said the government has decided to raise customs duty on
vehicles weighing over 10-tons from 10 to 20 percent to cover the
gap left by the abolished tax.
</P>
<P>
However, he warned that the people should be vigilant against
smuggling of the agricultural inputs imported into Tanzania,
where lack of tax is likely to led to lower prices.
</P>
<P>
The minister said interests of the farmers have been taken
into account in the 1997/98 budget.
</P>
<P>
"Taxes on mass consumer goods including textiles, shoes, soap
have gone down, tax on heavy duty tyres are down, tax on
pharmaceuticals down, in all these farmers stand to benefit," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
