<HEADLINE> Storms Leave Thousands of Capetonians Homeless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 28 (Xinhua) -- A heavy storm, the worst of
its kind in seven years, hit the Cape Peninsula Friday, leaving
some 4,500 people homeless, the local daily Citizen, reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Cape Town's homeless yesterday streamed to city shelters and the
salvation army urged residents to donate clothing, South African
Red Cross officials were quoted as reporting.
</P>
<P>
Red Cross spokeswoman Elsa Green said 3,500 people received
assistance and 60,000 Rand (13,333 U.S. dollars) was spent on blankets
and food following a storm Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Over the last week, unusually high tides combined with strong winds
have sent surf crashing through the plate-glass patio doors of
luxury sea-front homes in the Cape Town area.
</P>
<P>
Cape Town port captain John Woodend said work had been sporadically
disrupted all the week.
</P>
<P>
According to South Africa's Weather Bureau, the bitterly cold
weather, heavy rains and strong winds would continue, with snow in the
Peninusla Mountains. 
</P>
