<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hkhk - Hong Kong-related Data (17): Patten's "Triple Violation" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 28 -- On October 7, 1992, Chris Patten, the
newly appointed Governor of Hong Kong, delivered his first
political address at the Legislative Council, making major
alterations to Hong Kong's existing political system.
</P>
<P>
Patten's package violated the Sino-British Joint Declaration,
the principle of convergence with the Basic Law, and the relevant
agreements and understandings reached between the Chinese and
British governments. Hence it was called the "triple violation"
plan.
</P>
<P>
The first count of violation -- The British side undermined the
foundation of Sino-British cooperation, ignored the provisions for
consultation and cooperation in the Sino-British Joint
Declaration, and made unilateral arrangement for Hong Kong's
political system concerning the smooth transition in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The second count of violation -- The Basic Law provisions on
the formation of the government of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region take into full consideration the need of
gradual progress in Hong Kong's political system and reflect part
of the achievements in Sino-British cooperation, such as the
"through train" arrangement for Hong Kong's legislature.
</P>
<P>
However, Patten, in an attempt to force the Chinese side to
accept his political package with a fait accompli, altered the
function groups and the voting method of the election committee
for the legislature, thus derailing the "through train".
</P>
<P>
The third count of violation -- The Chinese and British foreign
ministers, through diplomatic letters, reached explicit agreements
and understandings in principle on the convergence of the
political system before and after 1997, especially the "through
train".
</P>
<P>
The British side disrespected these agreements and
understandings, dished up a different plan, and even went so far
as to deny the binding force of the agreements and understandings.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the British side's unilateral implementation of the
"triple violation" political package was, far from what it claimed
to "accelerate the pace of democracy", actually to maintain to the
maximum extent its influence on the government of the future Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
