<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hkhk - Hong Kong-related Data (18): "Through Train" Arrangement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 28 (Xinhua) -- "Through train" originally
refers to the express train running between Kowloon and Guangzhou,
a common means of transportation for Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
The first Legislative Council of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) ought to be formed after China
resumes the exercise of its sovereignty over Hong Kong in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government, out of concern for a smooth transition
in Hong Kong, and at the suggestion of the British side agreed
that members of the last Legislative Council produced by the
British Hong Kong authorities in 1995 may become members of the
first Legislative Council of the HKSAR after going through
specified legal procedures if the composition of this last
Legislative Council is in conformity with the relevant decision of
the National People's Congress (NPC) and the relevant provisions
of the Basic Law and if its members meet certain qualifications.
</P>
<P>
Since this arrangement, which is conducive to Hong Kong's
smooth transition, resembles the Kowloon-Guangzhou express train
in some respects, it is popularly called the "through train"
arrangement or "through train".
</P>
<P>
However, because the British side unilaterally pushed ahead
with its political package and the composition of the last
Legislative Council of the British Hong Kong authorities is not in
conformity with the relevant provisions of the Basic Law, the
basic conditions for implementing the "through train" arrangement
are destroyed.
</P>
<P>
As a result, members of the last Legislative Council of the
British Hong Kong authorities can not get on the "through train".
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "One Country, Two Systems" to Facilitate Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The concept of "one country, two
systems" is the best approach to the reunification of China, which
will also facilitate the solution of the Taiwan issue, Indonesian
Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said here today.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, Alatas said the idea of
"one country, two systems" put forward by late Chinese leader Deng
Xiaoping is realistic and many people hoped that the idea will be a
facility of reunification for China.
</P>
<P>
He said that the return of Hong Kong to China is a historical
event and a milestone not only in the history of China and Asia
but also in the history of the world at large. He was confident
that China has the ability to keep stability and prosperity of
Hong Kong in the future.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has played a very important role in the economic
development in East Asia and Southeast Asia, and as a member of
the APEC (Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum), it will
continue to keep its status both in Asia and the world.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that on the basis of the Joint Declaration
between China and Britain and the Basic Law, Hong Kong will
maintain its position as a free trade city and an international
economic and financial center for at least next 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Considering the mutual benefits, Indonesia and other countries
of the ASEAN (the Association of Southeast Asian Nations) are
willing to develop relations with Hong Kong, he said.
</P>
<P>
Alatas said the relations between Indonesia and China are very
good, especially in the economic field, since the resumption of
diplomatic ties in 1990.
</P>
<P>
At present, he said, Indonesia's trade with China is almost
four billion U.S. dollars and that with Hong Kong stands at two
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is the third largest investor in Indonesia with a
total of more than 16 billion dollars up to 1996, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
