<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strictly Observe the Hong Kong Basic Law (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By upholding a high degree of autonomy for the HKSAR, it means
to safeguard the provisions of the Basic Law that the HKSAR
"enjoys executive, legislative and independent judicial power,
including that of final adjudication." It means to respect the
practice of "Hong Kong being governed by the Hong Kong people",
which means that Hong Kong should be governed by "permanent
residents of Hong Kong" and that the government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region shall be composed of local people
with the people who love the motherland and Hong Kong as the main
body. The government may have the participation of other people
and also may appoint foreigners as advisors.
</P>
<P>
The Central People's Government will not interfere in the
efforts of the HKSAR to exercise administration and management
according to the provisions of the Basic Law. The Central
Government is responsible only for the foreign affairs relating to
and the defence of the HKSAR. All the affairs within the scope of
autonomy of the HKSAR will be free from interference by any
central department. There is no subordinate relationship between
central government departments and the corresponding departments
of the HKSAR government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strictly Observe the Hong Kong Basic Law (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By upholding a high degree of autonomy for the HKSAR, it also
means to handle correctly the relations between Hong Kong and the
inland. Inland provinces, autonomous regions, and municipalities
directly under central government are not allowed to interfere in
the administration of Hong Kong by the HKSAR government.
</P>
<P>
If they need to establish non-administrative organizations in
Hong Kong they must get the consent of the HKSAR government and
the approval of the central government.
</P>
<P>
The organizations established in Hong Kong by inland
institutions and their personnel must abide by the Basic Law and
laws of the HKSAR. Relations between the inland non-governmental
organizations and religious groups and their counterparts in Hong
Kong should be based on the principles of non-subordination,
non-interference, and mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
Trade and investment between Hong Kong and the inland will be
regarded as foreign trade and overseas investment. Their exchange
of financial operations is regarded as foreign financial
operations; their shipping operations are regarded as foreign
trade shipping. The exchange between Hong Kong and inland in trade
adn economic activities will basically follow the international
rules and common international practices; the disputes arising
from trade and economic activities will be handled according to
international rules.
</P>
<P>
The HKSAR has definite control line of boundary. In entering Hong
Kong, people from the other parts of the country must strictly
observe the related rules and go through the prescribed approval
procedures. In seeking permanent residence in the HKSAR, all the
related requirements of the Basic Law must be met. This is also an
embodiment of the concept of "one country, two systems".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strictly Observe the Hong Kong Basic Law (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By upholding the principle that will remain unchanged for 50
years, it means to maintain the principle of "one country, two
systems" unchanged for a long time to come and ensure that the
prevailing capitalist system and way of life in Hong Kong will
remain unchanged for a long period of time to come. Change in the
system and way of life will be unfavorable to Hong Kong and to
the long-term development of the whole Chinese nation.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with a delegation from Hong Kong and Macao
to the National Day celebrations in Beijing in 1984, Deng Xiaoping
said firmly: "Our policies will not change; no one can change
them, because these policies are correct and fruitful and have the
support of the people," and that "when we say that the policies
will remain unchanged for 50 years, we mean it. They will not
change in our generation; neither will they in the next."
</P>
<P>
The third generation of the Party leadership with Jiang Zemin
at its core is very firm in its determination to implement the
principle of "one country, two systems" and the Basic Law of the
HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
"To govern Hong Kong by law is an important part of our efforts
to govern China by law," said Jiang Zemin. "To uphold the
authority of the Basic Law is to uphold the authority of the legal
system of the country. This is the common duty of the Chinese
people."
</P>
<P>
The people of the whole country should make further efforts to
study the Basic Law of the HKSAR of the People's Republic of
China, acquire a thorough understanding of it, master it in an
all-round manner and abide by it consciously, and ensure a
long-term stability and prosperity of Hong Kong by the concrete
action of strictly observing the Basic Law. 
</P>
