<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Firms Stand to Gain From ITA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Information Technology
(IT) companies are standing to gain huge savings as the first
phase of the Information Technology Agreement (ITA), concluded in
March 1997, will be implemented beginning July 1 this year, the
Singapore Trade Development Board (TDB) said today.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore companies in the IT industry will gain an
accumulated potential tariff savings of more than 1 billion U.S.
dollars when the ITA is fully implemented in 2005, it said.
</P>
<P>
The ITA, first agreed upon at the inaugural World Trade
Organization (WTO) Ministerial Conference in Singapore in December
last year, will liberalize global trade in five main IT sectors,
namely computers, telecommunications equipment, semiconductors,
semiconductor manufacturing equipment and scientific instruments.
</P>
<P>
The IT market is estimated to be worth about 600 billion
dollars. Tariffs on IT products in most participating economies
will be completely eliminated by year 2000. However, some
developing countries have been allowed a longer time frame to
eliminate tariffs on some IT products, but in no case later than
2005.
</P>
<P>
After the Singapore WTO Ministerial Conference in December
1996, there were 29 original signatories to the ITA. The number of
ITA participants has since risen by another 15 signatories. There
are at present 44 signatories, covering more than 92 percent of
the global IT trade.
</P>
<P>
Ng Kim Neo, TDB senior director of trade policy, said,
"Singapore's participation in the ITA will provide our IT
exporters with more certainty and transparency when planning and
mapping their marketing strategies for the medium and longer
term."
</P>
<P>
The TDB said the Singapore companies are advised to contact the
TDB should they find that the ITA member countries they are
exporting to are not meeting the obligations of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
"The TDB will then assess the matter and act accordingly," it
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
