<HEADLINE> Transport Increases Between Hong Kong and Inland Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Transport volume between Hong
Kong and China's interior areas is increasing steadily, with the
number of cross-border vehicles rising five percent in 1996, local
sources said today.
</P>
<P>
According to government statistics, on average 1,900, 8,900 and
13,500 vehicles cross ports of entry at Sha Tau Kok, Man Kam To
and Lok Ma Chau each day, respectively. Some 91 percent of these
vehicle are trucks.
</P>
<P>
The Kowloon-Guangzhou Railway has also played a key role in
transportation between Hong Kong and the inland areas of China.
</P>
<P>
Last year, nearly 1.2 million tons of goods from the inland
areas were transported to Hong Kong through railway, while 800,000
tons of cargoes were shipped to the inland areas from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The number of passengers that crossed the border by train
reached 48 million in 1996, five million more than in the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, seven million people traveled between Hong Kong and
the interior areas by ferry last year. Hong Kong now has nine
ferry companies operating 28 routes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
