<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Central Bank Lowers Discount Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Italy's central bank has decided to
adjust its discount rate from the current level of 6.75 percent to
the new low of 6.25 percent effective from June 30.
</P>
<P>
Facilitating the 0.5 percentage point cut is the country's
increasingly steady economic growth, said Antonio Fazio, president
of the Bank of Italy, while announcing the decision.
</P>
<P>
Recent months have seen inflation being brought under control,
market demands increasing and productivity rising -- all positive
signs pointing to Italy's economic recovery, said Fazio.
</P>
<P>
The discount rate is the inter-bank rate charged by the central
bank against lendings to commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Bank of Italy's decision, Prime Minister
Romano Prodi said, "This is a piece of encouraging news."
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the Federation of Trade Unions and other groups also
spoke highly of the decision, saying it would help boost
investment and employment in both public and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate was down to 1.4 percent by the end of May,
the lowest in years, said the Central Institute of Statistics.
Electricity consumption in May was 4 percent more than that in the
same period of last year, indicating increased activities in
manufacturing sectors, said the National Bureau of Electricity.
</P>
<P>
The economic upturn has been much sought after by the
government policies designed to improve economic performances for
joining the European Union's single currency system.
</P>
<P>
Lowering the discount rate is no doubt beneficial to the
economic growth and the entry into the monetary union slated for
launch in 1999, when Euro will be the currency for all Europe.
</P>
<P>
Discount rate has been high in Italy over the past two decades,
with the highest of 19 percent recorded in January 1981. It
remained over 10 percent until July 1993, but still stayed as high
as 9 percent thereafter.
</P>
<P>
It was after nine downward adjustments in a row by the central
bank that the discount rate came down to the recent 6.25 percent,
or similar to that of 22 years ago in September 1975.
</P>
<P>
However, at the current level, the rate is still higher than
that of all the other West European countries except Britain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
