<HEADLINE> HK, India Sign Surrender of Fugitive Offenders Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong and India today signed
an agreement for the surrender of fugitive offenders which will
remain in force beyond 1997.
</P>
<P>
This is the eighth agreement Hong Kong has signed with foreign
countries in this important area of co-operation against
international crimes.
</P>
<P>
The other seven countries that have signed with Hong Kong are
namely the Netherlands, Canada, Australia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, the United States and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Today's agreement sets out the conditions for the surrender of
fugitive offenders between Hong Kong and India, and contains the
usual safeguards found in similar international agreements.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for Security Peter Lai signed the agreement today on
behalf of the Hong Kong government, and Veena Sikri, Indian
Consul-General in Hong Kong, signed on behalf of India.
</P>
<P>
"The agreement represents a milestone achievement in the
co-operation between India and Hong Kong in law enforcement," a
Hong Kong government spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement has been approved by the Sino-British Joint
Liaison Group and will remain in force after Hong Kong returns to
China on July 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
