<HEADLINE> Coxsackie Death Toll Rises to 30 in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Heart inflammation or viral
myocarditis, which is linked to the Coxsackie virus B, has claimed
its 30th victim in Sarawak, East Malaysia, According to Health
Minister Chua Jui Meng today.
</P>
<P>
The victim, an eight-month-old boy, died today at Sibu Hospital
in the East Malaysian state, the minister told reporters after a
function here.
</P>
<P>
The victim had fever and cough for two days and the diagnosis
was acute myocarditis, cardiogenic shock and aseptic meningitis,
Chua said.
</P>
<P>
On the overall situation, Chua said as of midnight yesterday
the total number of admissions was 2,140 cases with 1,770
discharged and 370 still warded in hospitals throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
As for Sarawak, where the outbreak started on April 14 and all
the deaths occurred, the total number of admissions to date was
733 cases with 657 discharged and 76 still warded, he said.
</P>
<P>
To a question on the control of the situation, the minister
said: "When we talk about controlling the further spread of the
disease it does not mean to say that the situation is controlled.
We are putting in preventive health measures on a massive scale to
control it from spreading to the entire population as this disease
can spread very fast..."
</P>
<P>
On the Sarawak front, he said the situation presented some hope
as the graph was coming down. "However, we may continue to see
deaths coming from different areas because Sarawak is a very
large state and the children are presented late," he added.
</P>
<P>
Chua reiterated his appeal to parents to act fast by bringing
their children to hospitals once they fell ill.
</P>
<P>
On how the viral myocarditis broke out, the minister said there
have been various surmises but to date it was not yet known if it
was local or foreign in origin.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
