<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Officials Hold Secret Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Minister of
Infrastructure Ariel Sharon and PLO Secretary General Abu Mazen
have recently held a secret meeting to discuss the stalled peace
process, reported the state-run Israel Radio today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting took place some 10 days ago at Sharon's desert
farm, south Israel and lasted for two and half hours.
</P>
<P>
Abu Mazen stressed the need for Sharon to meet with
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat. Sharon, a senior Likud
politician, has held various posts, including defense minister,
in different governments. Known for his hawkish view in the
party, the 69-year-old Likud politician has even recently called
Arafat "war criminal" and criticized other Likud leaders for
meeting with him.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Netanyahu is planning to shift him to
finance portfolio in a forthcoming cabinet reshuffle and allow him
to take part in the inner cabinet meeting dealing with security
matters.
</P>
<P>
Abdul Wahab Darawshe, Member of Knesset (parliament) and leader
of the Arab Democratic Party, helped set up the secret meeting. He
said that both men described the dialog as positive and agreed to
meet again in the future.
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian officials reportedly said that the meeting
was essential, but expressed unhappiness about a leakage of the
information. They attributed it to domestic political considerations
on the part of Israel.
</P>
<P>
The meeting happened at a time when the peace process has
broken off for more than three months since Israel began
construction of a new Jewish settlement at Har Homa in East
Jerusalem in mid-March. 
</P>
