<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysian CPO, Tin &AMP; Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of crude
palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week all
lower.
</P>
<P>
On the CPO physicals market, at the week close, June-South
stood at 1,210 ringgit (about 484 U.S. dollars) per ton against
1,222.5 ringgit (about 489 dollars) per ton at last week's close.
</P>
<P>
The CPO physicals trading is expected to be cautious as the
movement on the futures remained uncertain next week, dealers
said.
</P>
<P>
Players are expected to remain on the sidelines as they were
devoid of supportive fundamental factors in the market, a dealer
said, adding however that any strong movement on the futures
market would be the yardstick of the CPO physicals market's
performance.
</P>
<P>
This week, the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM) was lower to
close at 13.69 ringgit (about 5.48 dollars) per kg against 13.83
ringgit (about 5.53 dollars) per kg last week, following poor
support amidst weaker tin prices on the London Metal Exchange
(LME).
</P>
<P>
During the week, turnover rose to 524 tons against 487 tons
last week.
</P>
<P>
The KLTM's price differential to the LME stood at a premium of
45 dollars per ton from a premium of 55 dollars last week.
</P>
<P>
Bargain hunting might support falling tin prices next week,
dealers said.
</P>
<P>
Players were advised to trade cautiously, one dealer said,
adding that any further development on the LME, however, would
provide a significant impact to the trading activity.
</P>
<P>
Any buying now would be a wise decision as prices dropped, the
dealer said.
</P>
<P>
On the Malaysian rubber market, the week saw July RSS-One
tumbling 12.5 sen to close at 263.5 sen (about 105.4 cents) per kg
and SMR 20 plunging 8 sen to 276 sen (about 110.4 cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The International Natural Rubber Organization's (INRO) daily
market indicator price for June 26 stood at 197.97
Malaysia/Singapore cents (sen) per kg against 205.37 cents (sen)
on June 19.
</P>
<P>
The five-day moving average was at 201.58 cents per kg from
208.62 cents last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian rubber prices are likely to be bearish next week
because of the expected weak sentiment, dealers said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
