<HEADLINE> Nicaraguan Students Threaten More Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- After clashing with anti-riot
police Thursday, Nicaraguan students today vowed to hold more
demonstrations until the government meets their demand for keeping
the university budget intact.
</P>
<P>
Ten students and seven Sandinista deputies were injured in the
violence on Thursday afternoon after the National Assembly
approved President Arnoldo Aleman's veto on the university budget
with a reduction of 6 million U.S. dollars for public universities.
</P>
<P>
The National Council of Universities (CNU) said it will appeal
to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
The CNU said Aleman's veto will cause the loss of specific
projects for professional development, and the possibility of
granting scholarships to more poor students.
</P>
<P>
Student leader Julio Orozco said students will start a series
of demonstrations today, and they will not stop the protests
unless the government changes its attitude toward the universities.
</P>
<P>
National Police confirmed at a press conference this morning
that several students were detained during Thursday's
confrontation between 2,000 students and police.
</P>
<P>
The students raised barricades on Managua streets and occupied
the Radio Nicaragua building. 
</P>
