<HEADLINE> Chile Seeks Political Role in Mercosur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Chile is seeking a new agreement
with the South American Common Market (Mercosur) to secure the
country a place for political consultations within the bloc,
Chilean Foreign Minister Jose Miguel Insulza has said.
</P>
<P>
The "El Diario" newspaper today quoted Insulza as saying that
"there were big advances" in Chile and Bolivia's entry into the
regional group's political dialogue, but "now they must be
substantiated into a specific agreement."
</P>
<P>
Insulza said Chilean President Eduado Frei will travel to
Montevideo next month and "give a very clear expression of his
political will."
</P>
<P>
Established in 1991, Mercosur, initially consisting of
Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay, aims to intensify the
economic integrity of Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Heads of the member countries, together with presidents from
associate member countries of Chile and Bolivia, met in the
Paraguayan capital Asuncion on July 19, discussing a common
proposal to form a Free Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA).
</P>
<P>
Uruguayan President Julio Maria Sanguinneti has described
Mercosur as "a political alliance of six, which are united by free
trade and among four of them exists a common market." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
