<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 06:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Strongly Criticizes Turkish Parliament's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has strongly criticized a
Turkish parliament's decision to renew for another six months the
presence of the U.S. and British forces on Turkish territory.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency (INA) today quoted a Iraqi Foreign
Ministry spokesman as saying Friday that the decision made by the
Turkish parliament Thursday reflects what he called the Turkish
politicians' "deep neglect " of the real interests of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He added that the decision also reflects their insistence on
practicing the policy of bringing harm to Iraq and its national
security.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman asserted that Iraq holds Turkey fully
responsible for its "harmful" policy towards the country, which
confirms Turkey's "sorrowful non-respect" for the good
neighborliness relations with other countries, international law
and the U.N. charter.
</P>
<P>
The deployment of the U.S. and British troops on Turkish
territory to patrol the "no-fly" zone in northern Iraq have not
only threatened the security and sovereignty of Iraq but also that
of Turkey, stressed the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the renewal of foreign troops' presence
will help continue the "aggression" on Iraq and harms Turkey's own
interests.
</P>
<P>
After the 1991 Gulf War against Iraq ended, the U.S., France,
Britain and Turkey built a joint air force and set up a "non-fly"
zone in northern Iraq to protect Iraqi Kurds there from attacks
by Iraqi government troops.
</P>
<P>
The zone is patrolled at present by the U.S. and British
troops which have their bases in Turkey after France withdrew its
soldiers from the joint force at the end of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
