<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earth Summit Ends, Difference Unresolved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Nineteenth Special Session on
Sustainable Development ended here late Friday with major
differences unresolved.
</P>
<P>
The five-day meeting, known as "Earth Summit Plus Five",
reviewed progress after the Earth Summit held in Rio de Janeiro in
1992.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, heated discussions focused on three subjects --
official development aid to the developing countries, reduction of
greenhouse gases emissions and forests protection.
</P>
<P>
The developed countries agreed in principle in Rio to increase
aid to 0.7 percent of their gross national product. But it
declined from 0.35 percent to 0.27 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Despite severe criticism by the developing world, the West did
not make any commitment to live up to the commitment.
</P>
<P>
On the question of greenhouse gases, the United States has been
under attack right from the beginning of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
With its population accounting for only 2 percent of the
world's total, the United States produces more than 20 percent of
the greenhouse gases.
</P>
<P>
The European Union promised a 15 percent reduction in emissions
from the 1990 levels by 2010, with a 10 percent reduction by
2005. The United State, Canada and Japan made no commitments on
cutting the gases.
</P>
<P>
Canada and the European Union proposed to start negotiations
immediately on a binding treaty that would introduce standings for
the logging trade. But the proposal met opposition from the United
States, Brazil and India, which prefer to see existing agreements
enforced.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the diplomats attending the meeting managed to
adopt a final document, the Program for Further Implementing
Agenda 21, which "reaffirms that Agenda 21 remains the fundamental
program of action for achieving sustainable development."
</P>
<P>
"We are convinced that the achievement of sustainable
development requires the integration of its economic,
environmental and social components," the report said.
</P>
<P>
"We re-commit to work together -- in the spirit of global
partnership -- to reinforce our joint efforts to meet equitably
the needs of present and future generations," it said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. General Assembly President Ismail Razali said although
there were divisions among member states over the issue, the
session is a success because it serves as wake-up call on the
environmental dangers facing the world.
</P>
<P>
He said that after the meeting, all the countries should work
to live up to the requirements of the Agenda 21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
