<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico had a surplus of 5.3 billion U.S. dollars
in its trade with the United States during the first four months
of this year.
</P>
<P>
The favorable balance of payment was resulted from Mexico's
26.7 billion dollars exports to the United States and imports
worth 21 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- The prices of fuels will drop by 3.4 percent in
Costa Rica starting from July, the fourth reduction this year.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- More than 50 percent of Nicaraguans are unemployed
or underemployed, Nicaraguan President Arnoldo Aleman said.
</P>
<P>
Aleman said that the per capita income in his country is less
than 400 dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua, together with Haiti, are the poorest nations in the
American continent.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's exports to Mexico, the United States and
Canada, the three members of the North American Free Trade
Agreement (NAFTA), reached 1.16 billion dollars during the first
four months of this year, an 11 percent increase over the same
period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Chile's biggest market in North America was the United States
during the period, with exports amounting to 1.02 billion dollars,
a 7.8 percent rise over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Eighty-five percent of Venezuelans live under poor
living standards, according to a study of the Workers'
Documentation and Analysis Center.
</P>
<P>
The report said 15 percent out of the 85 percent is listed as
"absolute poverty," meaning they do not have enough money to buy
food, 40.3 percent as "extreme poverty" and 29.7 percent as
"relative poverty."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
