<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange ended lower this week as sellers dominated trading
despite the release of good corporate results.
</P>
<P>
During the week, the Composite Index fell 27.48 points to end
the week at 1,070.06, the Emas Index 6.5 points to 302.19, the
Industrial Index 63.34 points to 2,029.51 and the Second Board
Index 9.97 points to 565.95.
</P>
<P>
Finance counters were badly hit as interest rates went down
while the highly capitalized stocks did not get the necessary
support. Interest on second-boarders and lower liners remained
selective as players traded cautiously on concerns over
macroeconomic issues and the financial situation in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Constantly active throughout the week were four counters -- MBf
Capital which was relisted after the central bank rejected its
merger discussions with Suria Capital, Sriwani which announced
plans to be a leading wholesaler of tourism products, Taiping
Consolidated which was affected by rumors of a top corporate
figure buying its shares, and Maybank which was affected by
interest rate jitters.
</P>
<P>
The KLSE's mainboard volume was 1.119 billion shares worth
6.418 billion ringgit (about 2.57 billion U.S. dollars) from
923.215 million shares valued at 5.65 billion ringgit (about 2.26
billion dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
The second board turnover stood at 216.751 million shares
valued at 2.533 billion ringgit (about 1.01 billion U.S. dollars)
against 341.615 million shares worth 3.855 billion ringgit (about
1.54 billion dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
Off-market deals amounted to 305.284 million shares worth 2.157
billion ringgit (about 860 million dollars) compared with 181.781
million shares valued at 1.265 billion ringgit (about 510 million
dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
The top 10 stocks were Taiping with 137.335 million shares
traded, MBf Capital 108.815 million shares, Sriwani with 74.32
million shares, P&AMP;D 34.003 million shares, Malpac 32.736 million
shares, TCB-T 31.194 million shares, Renong 29.994 million shares,
Samanda 26.994 million shares, Orlando 19.183 million shares and
Eden 18.159 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Consumer products accounted for 53.531 million shares traded
while industrial products made up 132.212 million shares,
construction 123.207 million shares and trading/services 214.408
million shares. Infrastructure had 8.994 million shares traded,
finance 221.191 million shares, hotels 7.681 million shares,
properties 219.502 million shares, plantation 36.369 million
shares, mining 2.183 million shares, trusts 954,000 shares and
loan stocks 104.503 million shares.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
