<HEADLINE> U.N. Agency Vows to Help Least Developed Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Industrial Development
Organzation (UNIDO) will focus its efforts to help the world's
least developed countries, a senior official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Istvan Posta, a Hungarian diplomat who chairs the UNIDO Board
of Directors, told reporters that a relevant program of action was
worked out at the agency's just-concluded one-week board meeting.
</P>
<P>
Special attention will be given to the industrial development
of African nations, Posta said.
</P>
<P>
The board meeting also discussed the UNIDO's budget and
provided options of a 10 percent, 20 percent or 30 percent cut,
pending the board's decision at its next meeting in September.
</P>
<P>
However, UNIDO Director-General Mauricio de Maria y Campos
complained that the agency has found it hard to fulfill its
extensive mandate with restrained financial resources.
</P>
<P>
While condemning the U.S. withdrawal from the UNIDO as a breach
of its international commitment, he hoped that Germany and Britain
would not follow the suit and would continue to support the UNIDO.
</P>
<P>
At the board meeting in September, UNIDO officials are
scheduled to discuss finding a new leader for the U.N. agency, as
Campos' term expires at the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
