<P>
"Being public servants, we more or less have a sense of
historic mission to varying extent. We will feel contented as Hong
Kong progresses toward the good direction," she said in an
interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. K. Fok, 55, graduated from the University of Hong Kong in
1962, and became an administrative officer. To date, she has
served on more than 10 different posts over the past 35 years and
assumed her present post in 1994.
</P>
<P>
She is now in charge of the medical, welfare and hospital
divisions. The greatest advantage of this system of integrating
medical and health work and social welfare is to combine
prevention, treatment and convalescence, thus effectively
facilitating the protection of the people's health, she said.
</P>
<P>
Like other Hong Kong residents, Fok takes pride in the
sustained growth in Hong Kong's economy, which has resulted in the
effective growth of local medical and health work.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging that Hong Kong leads the Southeast Asia in the
development of public health, she said the region, with a
population of 6.3 million, has 8,000 registered physicians and
7,000 physicians practising traditional Chinese medicine, she
added.
</P>
<P>
While a complete legal framework has been formed for the
Western medicine, she said that as the next step, the relevant
government departments will focus their attention on popularizing
traditional Chinese medicine, drawing up a series of supervisory
regulations and training more traditional Chinese doctors.
</P>
<P>
In addition, she said, it is essential to explore new channels
to cut the rising cost of medical service brought about by the
aging of the local population.
</P>
<P>
She held that public health plays a vital role in maintaining
social stability. Therefore, she urged increased education on
health work and family sanitation so as to increase the awareness
of the residents on sanitation and health and enable their family
members to live in harmony. This is a kind of social welfare as
well as a contribution to social stability, she said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has more than 600,000 people at or above the age of
65, who make up one tenth of its total population. The figure is
expected to reach 800,000 in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
K. Fok pondered over a new concept in service of the elderly.
Local residents will, via education on how to keep fit, will come
to recognize the importance of enthusiastic involvement in
community life and self-study and giving scope to their
enterprising spirit in the process of slowing down the process of
the aging.
</P>
<P>
K. Fok advocates the fine traditional virtue of "respecting the
old and loving the young" and "Living in harmony" of the Chinese
nation. In spite of a host of homes set up especially for the
aged, she said, the best and most appropriate way is to let the
elderly people stay and live with their children, enjoying
themselves at their own homes.
Moreover, departments of health and social welfare, and various
societies and organization are also working for the service of the
aged, she said. And a great deal of work in the field of social
welfare needs the assistance and support of volunteers, who make
others feel the warmth of living in community.
</P>
<P>
As a career workman, K. Fok added, a female should plays the
part of a wife and the mother well at home, and he best option is
to work in close cooperation with the family members as well as
with colleagues or subordinates in office.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless," she said, "My lifelong career is to serve Hong
Kong."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
