<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Views Israeli Settlement Construction As "Serious" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan today said Israel was still continuing its construction of
the new settlement on the occupied territory, which was "viewed as
particularly serious."
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council, Annan noted that as of
last Friday, the Israeli government has not abandoned its
construction of a new Israel settlement at Jabal Abu Ghneim, south
of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Politically, Annan said, the start of building at Jabal Abu
Ghneim on March 18 "represents the first move to construct an
entirely new settlement on occupied Palestinian lands since a
freeze was imposed on such activities by the previous Israeli
government in the context of the peace process."
</P>
<P>
Geographically, it represents "the final link" in a chain of
settlements constructed by Israel around occupied East Jerusalem,
Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Demographically, the U.N. chief said, it would have a
"significant effect on further advancing the forced alternation of
the religious and ethnic composition of occupied East Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
Economically, it was "expected to have damaging effects on an
already devastated Palestinian economy in the occupied
territories," Annan noted.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said Israel's refusal to abandon construction at
Jabal Abu Ghneim "appears to represent, in the view of the
Palestinian people, the largest single negative factor in the
breakdown of the peace process, and the formenting of unrest on
the occupied territories."
</P>
<P>
An emergency special session of the U.N. General Assembly in
April demanded the immediate cessation of construction at the
site, called Har Homa in Hebrew and Jabal Abu Ghneim in Arabic.
</P>
<P>
The assembly resolution, adopted by a vote of 134 to three with
11 abstentions, also demanded a halt to all other Israeli
settlement activities and called for an end to all support for
"illegal Israeli activities" in the occupied territories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finance Institutions Ordered to Suspend Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Thai central bank and the
Finance Ministry Friday ordered 16 unhealthy finance institutions
to suspend their operations in a decisive bid to restructure the
ailing finance sector in the country.
</P>
<P>
The 16 finance and securities companies were ordered to suspend
their operations, including trading on the stock market, for 30
days and prepare merger plans within 14 days, or they will be
forced to join with Krung Thai Thanakit, a finance firm backed by
the state-run Krung Thai Bank, or other firms.
</P>
<P>
The 16 finance and securities companies, including prominent
listed ones like Finance One, General Finance and Securities, have
combined assets of more than 230 billion baht (9.2 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, the Finance Ministry said the depositors of the
suspended finance firms will be fully protected and they will be
allowed to withdraw their money, but under certain limitations.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the central bank said the 16 firms were singled
out for the forced action because their capital funds were not
higher than three-quarters of the registered capital or their
borrowing from the central bank had topped 40 percent of
outstanding deposits.
</P>
<P>
By law, these companies should be barred from taking deposits
from the public, they added.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers reported that the Thai government has named
some healthy companies to absorb these troubled institutions and
some investors described the move as "bold and decisive" in
revamping the country's troubled finance sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
