<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Remain One of Safest Places: Police Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's police chief said
Kong will remain to be stable and safe after its return to China
at midnight, June 30.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong will remain one of the safest and most stable places
in the world," said Eddie Hui Ki-on in an exclusive interview with
Xinhua. Hui is the current Commissioner of Police in Hong Kong and
will work in the same capacity for the future Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
The priority for the Hong Kong police at the moment is to
ensure security for the handover ceremonies to be attended by
world dignitaries as well as Chinese and British leaders.
</P>
<P>
The police chief vowed to ensure absolute security for
thousands of guests coming for the ceremonies from every corner of
the world, adding that the police have gone all out to prepare for
the ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
A veteran policeman, Hui joined the Hong Kong police in 1963
and served as inspector and assistant commissioner before being
appointed Commissioner in July 1994.
</P>
<P>
The return of Hong Kong to China represents a historic change
to the metropolis, but security and stability in Hong Kong will
not compromised in the least since its social and economic systems
will remain unchanged and since the police's commitment to make it
one of the safest places in the world will remain unchanged, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The police have made plans and set goals for the next five
years, he said.
</P>
<P>
The only change affecting the police, he said, will be the
removal of the word "Royal' from the name of the police force and
the replacement of the crown by a bauhinia, a flower representing
Hong Kong, on the police insignia.
</P>
<P>
After July 1, Hui emphasized, the Hong Kong police will
continue to enforce laws that are in conformity with the Basic
Law, and retain its membership in Interpol, while its staff will
continue to strictly follow professional and disciplinary codes.
</P>
<P>
"In one word, the police force will continue to carry out their
tasks with high professional standards and political neutrality to
safeguard Hong Kong's sustained stability and prosperity," the
Commissioner said.
</P>
<P>
He envisioned closer cooperation between the Hong Kong police
and their counterparts in China's inland areas, which has proved
to be quite successful over the past ten-plus years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
