<HEADLINE> Shenzhen-HK Cooperation Boosts SEZ's Power Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen and Hong Kong have
cooperated in building and running power plants over the past
decade, contributing to the fast growth of the power industry in
China's first Special Economic Zone (SEZ).
</P>
<P>
In 1987, the country's first foreign-funded power plant,
Shajiao B Power Plant, came into operation. It is
Build-Operate-Transfer (BOT) project between the Shenzhen SEZ
Power Development Company and a Hong Kong company.
</P>
<P>
In its operation to date, the station's two generator units,
each of 350,000 kw capacity, have produced 40.78 billion kwh of
electricity, easing the bottlenecked power supply in the booming
SEZ.
</P>
<P>
In the last two years, contracts to build two more power
plants, East Shenzhen and Qianwan, have been signed between
companies from the neighboring cities.
</P>
<P>
Planners say that the new plants will further improve the
power-supply network in Shenzhen as the SEZ enters its second
stage of development. Cooperation with Hong Kong, they say, has
greatly enhanced the reliability and safety of the power supply
network. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
