<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Consumer Goods Market To Remain Brisk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The consumer goods market is
expected to remain buoyant in the second half of this year taking
sales for the whole year beyond the target of 134 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
An official report attributes the booming consumer commodity
market to the improved macro-economic situation, rising demand and
surging investment in fixed assets.
</P>
<P>
Savings by local residents topped 250 billion yuan in May this
year, up 52 percent year-on-year, while exports rose by 11.6
percent in the first five months.
</P>
<P>
Both the return of Hong Kong and the Shanghai's hosting of the
Eighth National Games are expected to keep citizens in a spending
mood, while authorities have planned a number of commercial
activities to spotlight certain sectors by staging more than 50
international and national exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
However, the report also points out that several factors may
curb the bullish consumer market, such as the growing numbers of
jobless people, low-income families, stock investment, expected
price-hikes in apartment rents, water, power, coal, and the rising
charges of transport, education, medicine, insurance, recreation
and telecommunications. 
</P>
</TEXT>
