<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Parliament Approves 1997 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's parliament, known as the
Supreme Soviet, gave its green light to the country's 1997 budget
plan today after a nine-month scuffle with the government.
</P>
<P>
Approved by 229 to 71 votes, the annual budget calls for
revenues of 22.4 billion hryvnas (about 12.2 billion U.S. dollars)
and expenditures of 28.1 billion hryvnas (15.3 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit is estimated to be 5.7 percent of the gross
domestic product, which the government hopes to make up through
reduced cash circulation and increased issuance of treasury notes.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investments are also expected to be helpful for the
government's efforts to fill up the budgetary gap.
</P>
<P>
Also under the budget plan, the Ukrainian government will
allocate nearly 1.05 billion hryvnas (570 million dollars), or 4.7
percent of the national budget, to the defense sector.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 1.07 billion hryvnas (580 million dollars), or 4.8
percent of the total, will go to judiciary and national security
and 2.02 billion hryvnas (1.09 billion dollars), or 8.9 percent,
will go to the social welfare sector.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian parliament, which started to discuss the 1997
budget last September, was unhappy with the tax and pension reform
package included in the government-proposed budget plan.
</P>
<P>
It thus ignited a nine-month scuffle between the government and
the parliament. The deadlock not only forced a deputy prime
minister to resign, but also scared away many potential
investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
