<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donated Funds Help Disabled People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The China Fund for the Disabled
(CFFD) received 25.7 million yuan in donations and much material
support from the Chinese public and friends abroad last year.
</P>
<P>
"The donations went a long way to help its 60 million disabled
people last year," Deng Pufang, fund director, said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The fund was established in 1983 to promote the development of
undertakings for people with physical disabilities in China.
</P>
<P>
Deng told a meeting of the fund's board of directors in
Beijing, that CFFD spent 21.4 million yuan on rehabilitation
programs, education, employment, cultural and sports activities,
and the construction of basic facilities for the physically and
mentally disabled across the country.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to these efforts last year, Deng said, 257,170 cataract
sufferers regained their sight; 51,365 polio victims or those
suffering from spinal or joint problems received successful
operations; and 13,420 deaf children participated in hearing and
speech programs."
</P>
<P>
In addition, he noted, more than 24 million newly married and
pregnant women and babies took liquid iodine to prevent mental
diseases.
</P>
<P>
Education for handicapped children has also improved, with 112
new special schools opened, Deng said.
</P>
<P>
Local governments provided jobs for 240,000 people with
physical disabilities last year and arranged training courses for
185,000 disabled people to learn skills of farming, animal
breeding and household handicrafts businesses.
</P>
<P>
"These achievements have gone far beyond expectations, Deng
said.
</P>
<P>
The fund's budget for implementing this year's plans will be 15
million yuan, said Han Sheng, secretary-general of the fund.
</P>
<P>
"After about 10 years' efforts, China's undertakings for the
disabled are now switching towards an approach of sustainable
development, despite a weak basis," Deng said.
</P>
<P>
Disabled people are receiving more respect, understanding and
support from the public while many people with physical
disabilities have shown they are outstranding with their
achievement through unremitting efforts, said the official.
</P>
<P>
The Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000), worked out by the
Co-Ordination Committee for the Handicapped under the State
Council, will help the country's disabled people participate in
all aspects of social life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic-language Publications Mushroom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 28 (Xinhua) -- A minority like Ozbek, with just
more than 10,000 people in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region,
has its own books, teaching materials and other publications in
its own language.
</P>
<P>
Members do not need to bother reading other languages, thanks
to the fast development of publishing in ethnic languages.
</P>
<P>
Publication is also booming in more than 20 other ethnic
written materials, said today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
China is trying hard to publish more and better books for
ethnic people, according to the Third Ethnic Book Prize Giving
Ceremony yesterday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic books publishing is an important part of the country's
publication career, the Beijing-based English paper quoted Yu
Youxian, director of the State Press and Publication
Administration, as saying.
</P>
<P>
In the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000), 57 kinds of ethnic
books have been listed as national key publications to be given
priority. It is more than double that in the Eighth Five-Year Plan
(1991-1995).
</P>
<P>
To help solve financial difficulties facing ethnic language
books publication, the administration and State Ethnic Affairs
Commission last year set up the National Five Ethnic Books
Publication Fund.
</P>
<P>
By the end of April, more than 150 publishing houses had
subscribed to donate more than 8.2 million yuan (1 million US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Ten million yuan (1.2 million dollars) is expected by the end
of this year and the fund will be used then, Yu said.
</P>
<P>
The country is increasing its investment in ethnic books
publication each year. In a market economy, ethnic books
publication, with small circulations, is severely challenged.
</P>
<P>
The central and local governments' allocations and the new fund
will finance the publication of ethnic books.
</P>
<P>
In another development, ethnic language publication houses are
encouraged to explore international markets, as part of their
efforts to survive and develop.
</P>
<P>
In China, ethnic language books are not limited as they are for
general books. They also do not pay for bar codes and enjoy many
other priorities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
