<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Razali Says There Will Be No Political Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- U.N. General Assembly
President Ismail Razali said today that there will be no political
statement from the week-long U.N. special session on sustainable
development.
</P>
<P>
He said nevertheless the special session will adopt a final
document, to be known as Program for Further Implementation of
Agenda 21. Many issues will be contained in that document.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference near the end of the 19th U.N.
special session, which is designed to review the progress since
the Rio Earth Summit in 1992, President Razali acknowledged that
there are serious divisions between the 173 delegations on such
topics as financial targets for helping poor countries meet
environmental goals, greenhouse gases emission and protection of
forests, etc.
</P>
<P>
The failure to have a political statement "underlines how
difficult it is to capsulize issues in that context when over five
years we have not enough progress on some of the issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
Most industrial countries pledged at Rio to increase foreign
aid to 0.7 percent of their gross national product, a goal on
the U.N. agenda since 1972. But aid has fallen to 0.25 percent,
especially in the United States.
</P>
<P>
On greenhouse gases reduction, the European Union proposed a
15 percent reduction in emission below the 1990 level by 2010.
The United States, Canada, Australia and New Zealand want no
specific targets at this time. The final document will probably
call for "realistic targets" by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of forests, the United States, Brazil and India
opposed a treaty, preferring first to see existing agreement
enforced. Canada and the European Union, however, want the treaty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
