<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Talks Fail to Ease Parade Tension in N.Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The talks between rival parties in
Northern Ireland in a bid to reduce tensions have failed to
achieve their goal after an eight-hour discussion, a British
senior official said today.
</P>
<P>
"While we have not reached a resolution today, there are a
number of areas which I want to consider further," Britain's
Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"I shall do this and be in touch again with both sides early
next week," she added.
</P>
<P>
The talks between Roman Catholics and Protestant parade
organizers were held earlier today near the provincial capital
Belfast under the sponsorship of the British government. The
Catholics were strongly against the parade due to start on July 6
by the pro-British Protestants.
</P>
<P>
Both sides said they wanted a peaceful resolution to the
controversy over the parade in Portadown, a town where sectarian
tensions run high.
</P>
<P>
The Catholics blamed the Protestants for failing to reach
agreement Orange Order, saying it had refused to talk to them face
to face.
</P>
<P>
But the Protestants, who say their Portadown parade is a simple
demonstration of religious faith, issued a statement saying they
had put forward "responsible and accommodating principles which
respect the rights of everyone."
</P>
<P>
Britain fears that any trouble at the Portadown parade could
ignite violence across the province. A bloody clash erupted last
year during the parade season between the Roman Catholics and
Protestants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
