<HEADLINE> Pentagon Denies Having Secret Weapons Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Defense Department
today denied a lawmaker's charge that it had a secret fund of 20
billion U.S. dollars for future weapons purchases.
</P>
<P>
Norm Dicks, a senior member of the House Appropriations defense
subcommittee, produced a summary sheet showing that the Pentagon
intends to use the "modernization reserve" fund from 2000 to 2003.
</P>
<P>
"This account is highly unusual, unlike any other contained in
prior budget submissions to Congress," said Dicks, who has served
for 20 years on the defense spending panel.
</P>
<P>
He said it "proves that the Pentagon was deceiving Congress
about the availability of out-year funding in its budget."
</P>
<P>
"We didn't have any secret fund," said Susan Hansen, a Pentagon
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
"It's public knowledge. The money has now been passed to the
services to include in their budget submissions," she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
