<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Sets Its Own Salmon Quotas After Talks Fail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government today
announced its own fishing plans for this year's Pacific salmon
fishery after the collapse of salmon talks with the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the lack of an agreement with the U.S., it is
necessary now to move forward with management plans that will
conserve fish stocks and attend to the needs of our fishing
communities," said David Anderson, Canadian minister of fisheries
and oceans.
</P>
<P>
"Americans can no longer rely on Canada's good will to
accommodate their interests. It will not be business as usual,"
Anderson noted in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Under the quotas announced today, the total Canadian commercial
catch of all five species of salmon in 1997 is expected to be
nearly 24 million fish.
</P>
<P>
The potential Canadian catch of sockeye is expected to be 12
million, significantly higher than the 10-year (1983-94) average
of 9.9 million sockeye.
</P>
<P>
Canada estimates that over 18.2 million sockeye will return to
the Fraser River this year, the second highest return on record
since 1913.
</P>
<P>
Yet, Anderson stressed that conservation of salmon is Canada's
"top priority." He called on the United States to "fish
responsibly."
</P>
<P>
The latest round of talks between Canada and the U.S. broke
down last week.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. rejected Canada's final offer on salmon, which
included a reduced Canadian coho catch in return for a reduced
American sockeye catch.
</P>
<P>
Canada has said that it will push for third-party binding
arbitration to settle the dispute, the only option available after
the failure of several different processes.
</P>
<P>
But the U.S. has been cool to the idea. An attempt at
non-binding arbitration collapsed two years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
