<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Not to Give Up Affirmative Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
told a leading Hispanic group today that he refuses to give up on
affirmative action and wants to make sure the budget agreement
with Congress does not shortchange education.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, in a satellite speech to the League of United Latin
American Citizens, said, "I'm not willing to give up on
affirmative action and education. I'm not about to give up on it,
and we are exploring what our legal options are, as well as what
policies we might implement to try to stop public higher education
in America from becoming resegregated."
</P>
<P>
The president said that affirmative action students "have done
very, very well in the universities of our country," and also
improve the quality of education there for other students by
diversifying the student body.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said a key to ensuring minority enrollments is to reach
at risk students at the elementary and secondary school levels
before dropping out becomes a possibility.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the 110,000-member group meeting in Anaheim,
California, to become part of his national dialogue on race.
</P>
<P>
"Hispanic Americans must be a big part of this initiative," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Latinos represent the youngest and the fastest growing
population in our nation," Clinton said. "In many ways, America's
success depends upon Hispanic success." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
