<DOCNO> XIE19970628.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Congress Approves Huge Tax Cut Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate approved today
a tax cut plan of 135 billion dollars for the next five years, the
biggest tax cut in 16 years.
</P>
<P>
The 80-18 vote in the U.S. Senate came a day after the U.S.
House of Representatives passed a similar tax-cut package by a
vote of 253-179.
</P>
<P>
The bill contains a total tax cut of 135 billion dollars that
are partially offset by 50 billion dollars of new revenue. And the
net tax cut for the next five years for American families will be
85 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The 718-page bill passed in both the U.S. House and Senate
provides a 500-dollar tax credit for children under age 17, tax
breaks for education, a reduction in capital gains taxes, expanded
Individual Retirement Accounts and relief from estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
Roughly similar to the Senate version, the House bill departs
in significant areas, which will be the focus of still more
negotiations between Congress and the White House later this
summer.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Senate also turned back today a move to further raise
cigarette taxes before the final vote, killing an amendment to add
23 cents more to the tax on a pack of cigarettes. The proposal
would have raised another 12 billion dollars for health coverage
for uninsured children from poor families.
</P>
<P>
A compromise version of the tax cut plan will be written by
House and Senate tax writers next month, and the final bill could
be sent to President Bill Clinton for his consideration by August.
</P>
<P>
Talks between the Congress and the government on the tax cut
plan began almost immediately after the passage of the tax bill in
the U.S. House. U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and White
House lobbyist John Hilley met privately with the main tax writer
in the House, Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer, Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At the White House, press secretary Mike McCurry has expressed
confidence that the talks will produce a final measure more to the
president's liking than either the Senate and House versions.
</P>
<P>
But McCurry said that if the administration's efforts fail,
President Clinton will veto legislation that blows a hole in the
deficit.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic alternative to the bill approved by the
Republican-controlled Congress would extend the 500-dollar child
credit to millions of working families excluded in the Republican
plan because they had already taken the Earned Income Tax Credit,
which is aimed at helping the working poor. The Democratic plan
also offered narrower capital gains reductions and targeted them
to assist small businesses.
</P>
<P>
The tax cut initiative is one of the major part in the balanced
budget agreement reached earlier this year between the Clinton
administration and the U.S. Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
